Support building wheels (PEP-427)

With that, building and uploading wheels to PyPI is only one "python
setup.py bdist_wheel" away.

commit_message:
declares the max_size parameter in more functions

Commit f6810be4, Change-Id: I3d47adaa2ad07434853f447feb27d7aae0e2e717,
introduced a max_size parameter.

This patch define the parameter for _create_swap() and
_create_ephemeral() to avoid:

    foo() got an unexpected keyword argument 'max_size' errors.

test: _create_swap() is called with run_as_root=True even if mkswap do
not require root privilege. Doing this help to be sure the test-suite
won't be broken if the user do not have /sbin in the $PATH.

Fixes bug: 1250032
Fixes Bug: 1251152

Change-Id: I16e51669fedfd0cf3f01fb4c383dfa7d3595e015

commit_message:
Adding guard around deleting sqlite db

    * Don't delete if node.openstack.db.identity.db_type is set to sqlite

Fixes: bug #1251044

Change-Id: I8912808f2858e75c26bab39a0e61662bc63dd495

commit_message:
Swift packages should be optionally installed.

Create a subset of swift packages to be installed only
if asked for by the default_store attribute.
Added unit tests for ubuntu and redhat.

Change-Id: I8ed5d543d87b180148e0aa4b556ab8cbc4802f2e

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-04 15:20:27.000000000', 'message': 'Ensure anti affinity scheduling works

The query for the group in the system_metadata would not correctly
filter the instances with the groups.

In addition to this change 4a03071db23196c4ac1ec0d8ea163c46887d3b08
ensured that the scheduling filter was only run once.
In cases when provisioning fails and rescheduling
takes place the filter must be invoked (if it is in the filter tool
chain).

Fixes bug: 1218878
Fixes bug: 1206502

Conflicts:
        nova/db/sqlalchemy/api.py
        nova/tests/db/test_db_api.py

Change-Id: I623c73635c36ffa038ae01476a25ba0c0863e536

commit_message:
Ensure anti affinity scheduling works

The query for the group in the system_metadata would not correctly
filter the instances with the groups.

Fixes bug: 1218878

Conflicts:
        nova/db/sqlalchemy/api.py
        nova/tests/db/test_db_api.py

Change-Id: I623c73635c36ffa038ae01476a25ba0c0863e536
(cherry picked from commit 4233e16ba2f5bb85e93494b6eeb9ffff31dbdf30)

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-17 09:10:54.000000000', 'message': 'Fixing wrong number of arguments bug in ec2 api tests

boto has different implementations of get_http_connection
in different versions
Using newer versions (>2.14) is failing ec2 tests, as it is passing
wrong number of arguments to the method.
Fixing this by using parse_version

Fixes bug 1240342

Change-Id: I9f79f8868e2d7c3e39e01645c825a6d7f4a12a02
'}, {'created': '2013-10-19 06:52:19.000000000', 'message': 'Fixing wrong number of arguments bug in ec2 api tests

In boto version < 2.14.0 -> method new_http_connection
takes exactly two arguments
In boto version = 2.14.0 -> method new_http_connection
takes exactly three arguments
If the unit tests are run with a version of boto < 2.14,
tests fail with the error: "new_http_connection
does not take 2 or more positional arguments"

Fixing this by using parse_version on both
sides of the comparison of versions

Fixes bug 1240342

Change-Id: I9f79f8868e2d7c3e39e01645c825a6d7f4a12a02
'}]
commit_message:
Fixing wrong number of arguments bug in ec2 api tests

In boto version < 2.14.0 -> method new_http_connection
takes exactly two arguments
In boto version = 2.14.0 -> method new_http_connection
takes exactly three arguments
If the unit tests are run with a version of boto < 2.14,
tests fail with the error: "new_http_connection
does not take 2 or more positional arguments"

Fixing this by using parse_version on both
sides of the comparison of versions

Fixes bug 1240342

Change-Id: I9f79f8868e2d7c3e39e01645c825a6d7f4a12a02

commit_message:
Improves Usability for Default Quotas Tab

The table in the Default Quota Tab has been rearranged to match the
Edit Project dialog in Quota Tab.This a partial fix to the bug
since some fields are missing as there is no support for Neutron
default quotas yet. The spellings have been fixed in the current
master release.

Fixes Bug: 1210533

Change-Id: I461976d2d21369b770bcbb2511a92816f36f2c2f

'}, {'account_id': 406, 'date': '2013-11-06 17:04:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Do not merge

First,
I would suggest not to change default passwords to any other complication.

Second, user may choose anything for a password - "admin", any number which would be same as some other setting. So it basically means that this is not the right approach to do. Let's bring this up to fuel-dev mailing list so we can collaboratively agree on the possible solution which will not be such a destroying to the user.'}, {'account_id': 406, 'date': '2013-11-06 17:14:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

"}, {'account_id': 3009, 'date': '2013-11-06 18:58:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

The only reasonable way to improve the case is to have somewhere (file, database, etc) a set of lines which are not password separators to avoid filtering them out. For example we encounter combinations like "fooSENSITIVEbar" and "oofSENSITIVErab". If we know that foo-bar is not a sensitive data separator then we won't touch this line even one of our passwords is 'SENSITIVE' while all other sequences will be filtered. It is a bit like data mining which is not very good when we are talking about security.
Is this ok?

Another way I would suggest is to avoid human readable passwords at all. Let's make all our passwords strong. Let's check passwords for their strength before we put them into database.

BTW, I don't think that here we need to pay much of our attention (filtering out passwords). We'd better avoid writing sensitive data in log files or in the a database at all.'}, {'account_id': 8789, 'date': '2013-11-11 10:21:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Do not merge

Ok, we need change logic.'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-11-19 06:03:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Migrate from nosetest to testr

This patch migrates from nosetest to tester. A couple of reasons bellow:

    * Parallel tests
    * Better integration with OS gates
    * Nosetest sometimes do crappy things :D

Some tests were renamed in this patch because they are broken and
somehow didn't showed up in the previous reviews - looks like something
related to nosetest.

Change-Id: I3c8370119e17bd78151cf67bbb99931e18e3cd73

commit_message:
Whitebox nova servers - base tests

This provides whitebox tests that were before held in
tempest.
Instance is created direct in the db (using the db api)
and further deleted in the compute api and passing through
the manager api. The idea is to stub only the necessary methods
as rpc calls.
Tests will pass over different states (vm_states and task_states)
and verify actions are performed as expected.

Partial fixes: bug 1222852

Change-Id: I0b27a29ed02f29463e4c4e39f711d39c88382c96

commit_message:
Modify to check response code of Swift API specifically

Replace assert statements with ones which check specific response
code for each Swift API, according to real Swift behavior.

Add some assert statements of checking response code to a few
test cases which do not include a response code checker.

commit_message:
Change generic NotFound exception to ImageNotFound

In case an image could not be found, an ImageNotFound exception will be raised, instead of a generic NotFound exception, in order to make sure that it is
an Image that couldn't be raised. However this does not apply if Image Metadata or Image Members could not be found, in those cases the NotFound exception
will still be raised. Changes have been made to the Exception class adding an ImageNotFound exception, places where the NotFound exception is used and the
given testcases.

Closes Bug: 1247633

Change-Id: I05ce02e983f038e57b579ee79ec0ac80ca63374b

commit_message:
Fix inconsistency between Nova-Net and Neutron

The neutron client raises NeutronClientException (status_code 404)
that is not unknown for nova, and is translated in 500 computeFault.
Catching this exception in nova/nova/network/neutronv2/api.py and
raising more generic exception as exception.NotFound solves the problem.

Added also an unitary test to test neutronv2 api

bug #1160309
bug #1200175

(cherry picked from commit 4a2915b4e389bfba0ff25583369fd75b24e19118)

Conflicts:
	nova/network/quantumv2/api.py

Change-Id: Ib2f1a0d49a12114b28f0cd5ce0bb7119f864d1a6

'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2013-10-09 11:35:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Are we sure there is no way a string literal can be sent to this function anywhere in the openstack stack? My experience with pg testing in the past is we are leaking bad types down all the time.

So if we are defining a contract on this function, we should do it, and reject with a well understood error wrong types. Not just change the tests to not tickle this issue."}, {'account_id': 6849, 'date': '2013-10-09 13:42:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Ok, so this is a really controversial one...

We can add a bunch of if blocks checking types of functions arguments. But is this the right way to go?

First, if we decided to do so, we would need to add type checking to all functions for the sake of consistency. 

Second, adding of such checks to DB API functions would bring a lot of boilerplate code make them less readable (+ this is error-prone).

Personally, I prefer to divide systems in layers, so there is a separate layer ('bridge') which handles all users input, does parsing, check values data types (maybe even values themselves, if it's possible). All layers behind 'bridge' layer don't care about of data types - they are meant to be correct, it's a 'safe' zone. Values loaded from DB or another persistent storage are meant to be correct to, as we had checked them before persisting at 'bridge' layer.

In WSGI apps like Nova API, there is a natural place to do validation of users input - resource controllers. Also this is the place where we can return meaningful errors to users.

So I would really like us to do validation of data types in API controllers and treat DB API layer as a 'safe' zone. That would allow us to keep DB API functions code readable and simple.

Thoughts?"}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-10-17 06:03:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Abandoned

commit_message:
Fix type mismatch errors in NetworkTestCase

A few tests of NetworkTestCase use string literals as
network_id values. This works great when running tests
on both SQLite and MySQL, but fails on PostgreSQL, which
is very string when checking data types.

Blueprint: db-api-tests-on-all-backends

Change-Id: I090e42ff045379ac404e7bc5c91fbc82a52920b0

commit_message:
Adds XML namespace example for disk config extension

Adds XML namespace and specifying of the disk config value
to the disk config extensions api sample test data for server
creation. This is being done so the api samples used by the
documentation contain the example of this usage.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Icd7aa3743f71dd1cb8575605e5f1ce5da6bd37bf
Closes-Bug: 1189817

commit_message:
Change capabilities filters to use resource type

A recent change in scheduler/filters/capabilities_filters.py added log
message, however since this filter is supposed to accommodate both Nova
and Cinder capabilities, the 'instance_type' should be 'resource_type'.

Change-Id: I21ccd7b628009aaf5db4af896b64b73fb6c40fe0

commit_message:
Update openstack/common/lockutils

The following commits are in this update:

79e6bc6 fix lockutils.lock() to make it thread-safe
ace5120 Add main() to lockutils that creates temp dir for locks
537d8e2 Allow lockutils to get lock_path conf from envvar
d498c42 Fix to properly log when we release a semaphore
29d387c Add LockFixture to lockutils
3e3ac0c Modify lockutils.py due to dispose of eventlet
90b6a65 Fix locking bug
27d4b41 Move synchronized body to a first-class function
15c17fb Make lock_file_prefix optional
1a2df89 Enable H302 hacking check
b41862d Use param keyword for docstrings
b873454 Added convenience APIs for lockutils
120ddef Improve Python 3.x compatibility
88d316f Locking edge case when lock_path does not exist
21925b6 Fix locking issues in Windows
547ab34 Fix Copyright Headers - Rename LLC to Foundation

Change-Id: Ie9b99ed80d603bdc7459ff7e25e3fba919429216

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-12 20:38:08.000000000', 'message': "Set a floor on the python-memcache library

python-memcache prior to version 1.48 will leak memory due to always
caching cas ids (compare and set) and with nothing designed to clean
it up.  In 1.48 it was changed to require a boolean argument 'cache_cas'
on init to enable the cas id caching.  In the case of keystone, we rely
on the cache_cas argument and cas functionality.  Ideally, all uses of
memcache should use later than 1.47 to prevent the memory leaking of
cas id caching.

Change-Id: Ide780e30a8243cd5fcc693515ffd84dfea3a3467
"}]
commit_message:
Set a floor on the python-memcache library

python-memcache prior to version 1.48 will leak memory due to always
caching cas ids (compare and set) and with nothing designed to clean
it up.  In 1.48 it was changed to require a boolean argument 'cache_cas'
on init to enable the cas id caching.  In the case of keystone, we rely
on the cache_cas argument and cas functionality.  Ideally, all uses of
memcache should use later than 1.47 to prevent the memory leaking of
cas id caching.

Change-Id: Ide780e30a8243cd5fcc693515ffd84dfea3a3467

  instances of Fault rather than webob.Response

commit_message:
Added logging in taskmanager models && _() strings

Gone through taskmanager models, addding a few debugging statements to
some methods; should help operations teams find various instance task
timings.   Also made sure *every* logging statment used the _() method
and that it's consistent throughout the taskmanager model.

Change-Id: I07a58ecd1a7de0d6f998c7b263f86eb766973221

commit_message:
Run generate_sample.sh as part of tox tests

Right now there is no guarantee that any changes to the sample
config generation code actually work.  Even though Oslo doesn't
need a sample config, run the script anyway to at least catch
major errors.

Change-Id: If63f84184c459bc3e2245b7fde19362140243894

commit_message:
Fix error when no custom config file matches *.conf.sample

In generate_sample.sh, an error will be raised when no custom config
files match '$BASEDIR/tools/config/*.conf.sample', because CONCAT_FILE
will be set with value '$BASEDIR/tools/config/*.conf.sample'.

for CONCAT_FILE in $BASEDIR/tools/config/*.conf.sample; do

    cat $CONCAT_FILE >> $OUTPUTFILE

done

This path will check match result first to avoid the error.

Closes-Bug: #1251297
Change-Id: I4bb2036b1d385e8f7621cbd8b14134f12618230d

commit_message:
Ensure all "os" values are valid/recognized

Added a check to ensure that all "os" values are valid/recognized. The
list of recognized values is contained in a global and can be updated
if/when we add any further operating systems.

Note that "adminuser" and "enduser" values are also included as
recognized as they are required by the user guides at this time.

Change-Id: I3303b9cb880b70cbf8298eecafc56dffe2276476

commit_message:
Install guide: rework the ceilometer section

* misc editing details (spacing, formatting, capitalization, replaceable
  data)
* give configuration file examples where possible
* reduce the delta between distributions to make things more easily
  maintainable (and possibly clearer)

commit_message:
setting correct configuration file

The metering_secret in the section publisher_rpc should be set
in /etc/ceilometer/ceilometer.conf and not in
/etc/keystone/keystone.conf.

backport: havana

Change-Id: Idb92b94599def85452da6397aaa056d2363667e7
(cherry picked from commit 379114885d09e51d1010e0b7ece0dc8e81cda49b)

Add the platform to the rest API

This adds only the very basic attributes to the Platform
class and more will be added as the the other definitions
are added.

commit_message:
Changes power_state and adds last_error field

Made these changes:
* power_state -- always represents current power state.
Any power operation sets this back to "actual" when done
(whether successful or not). It is set to ERROR only when
unable to get the power state from a node.

* target_power_state -- represents the requested destination
of a state transition. Cleared when the transition window is
over (whether successful or not).

* last_error -- string field used to store the last error from
any requested asynchronous operation (eg, whether that was to
change power state, or deploy a node, or anything else) that
started but failed to finish. Cleared when any new asynchronous
operation is started.

Closes-Bug: #1237688

Change-Id: I7e079627b87b2cb1606e677e287dd08dcc87263a

commit_message:
modify nova.conf.erb for allinone install in vm

When nova boot a vm in one VM, it will failed.
We set 'libvirt_cpu_mode=none' and
'libvirt_use_virtio_for_bridges=false' to make it
work well.

Change-Id: Ia517d5af4aeed0f42c04a4ff0de6ca4f3a53575a
Closes-Bug: #1228609

commit_message:
Added some more vagrant testing steps

Also added `$` to front of all sample shell commands.
* Helps ensure user knows it is a command to be run from CLI
* Also discourages bulk copy/paste running of the commands directly from example ( bad practice! )

Change-Id: I7484d77dc3575bb9784ffa6b44437a4f02c63cc8

commit_message:
Add all devstack nova instance types to F19 WordPress_NoKey

Add the m1.micro, m1.nano, and m1.xlarge instance types to the
WordPress_NoKey sample.  In the process, any devstack type that
requires atleast 2048MB of ram are mapped to i386 images, and those
requiring more are mapped to x86_64 images.

Change-Id: I48e696697436cfc820a91aa2096c94aec06cd769

commit_message:
Added admonition about .ini files

In Heat and Nova sections, where it is recommended to edit an .ini
file, added an admonition about using .ini files general configuration
tasks.

Change-Id: I64cc6edfa9704694961aa80dbb463c707938e381
backport: havana
Closes-bug: #1250304
(cherry picked from commit b6b5fd2b6d38e116961a21cfa037319f1f125451)

commit_message:
Add Glance support

Glance support in Cinder is used to convert images into volumes
or send volumes into Glance with the goal to boot virtual machines
from volumes.

Change-Id: Ie2c9ed382254e374d12242edc7d57077fbbcd240
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

commit_message:
Accessing a subresource that parent does not exist

When accessing a subresource like /nodes/<id>/ports or /chassis/<id>/nodes
where <id> does not exist should fail with 404.

Also fix a typo in the name of a method on test_nodes.py

Change-Id: I5b6beba00fa7cc72b45689c5685914da895b7aa2
Closes-Bug: #1246731

commit_message:
Externalization of heat template

Reasons: preparing trove to support multi-datastores
Changes: template loading, heat-support update

This code refactors the earlier code of instance creation using heat.

- Configuration templates stored at trove/templates/(datastore_type)/config.template
- Heat templates are stored in trove/templates/(datastore_type)/heat.template
- One template per datastore type
- New parameter - ImageId
- Removed SSH key parameter
- All resources are updated according to available OS resources
  (for more details please visit heat repository).

Author: Denis Makogon (dmakogon) <dmakogon@mirantis.com>
Co-Authored-By: Nilakhya Chatterjee (SnowDust) <nilakhya.chatterjee@globallogic.com>

Change-Id: Ie6863a625e1525e152ed2886a630dc4f233be8dc
Implements: blueprint provide-custom-heat-templates-for-each-service-in-trove

commit_message:
Add new type for swiftdevices

Swift devices consist of a zone, region, host, port and device, if they
are passed into swift hosts via heat metadata we can now verify them as
native types.

Closes-Bug: #1252165

Change-Id: I8681e36a0b02f62e4856e42ef1900ce4888cb305

commit_message:
Remove os="cirros" attribute

As there is no Cirros specific edition of the guide, and it's unlikely
there ever will be one, this note will never actually be displayed. This
change removes the attribute and rephrases the text of the node slightly.

Change-Id: I21ea1244e9e95ac7de25417a391a4909397a61aa
backport: havana
(cherry picked from commit eb22c6aecb6631b7882167987361ae821d99cce6)

commit_message:
use new network roles to update the role os-network

The current os-network.rb is based on the recipe of each network
component.Currently, there are some new roles for each network
component. So I use the new network roles to update the role
os-network.

Change-Id: I6b705b9ff307e08089e6d31a5b57825c22fd0348
Closes-Bug: #1243997

This commit will cause swift to be used as a backend to glance
if the heat metadata glance.backend = swift.

commit_message:
Add metadata to configure swift

o Adds the required swift metadata (in swift-source.yaml).
o Sets up glance to use the swift backend on the overcloud.
o Sets up glance to use the file backend on the undercloud and seed,
  i.e. maintain the Status quo.

Change-Id: I4a70ffbf9c51f1fea5cfc84d8718d3d30d36b3f2

commit_message:
Update swift element to install from source

The previous swift element only installed the swift package but didn't
setup anything beyond that.

This update results in 3 elements
swift         : common swift element
swift-proxy   : installs a swift proxy server
swift-storage : installs a swift storage server

Change-Id: I0b7eb4ce1d3d82fd4cf224f572f111d6801fac08

commit_message:
Respect the preset permissions of config files

It's sometimes desirable to specify the permissions or ownership of the
generated config file instead of setting the default 644 root:root.

If the file is already present, os-apply-config will just update the
contents and leave everything else alone.

Closes-Bug: #1246266
Change-Id: Idd41ec276dd04f517760c1dbd97c75e376840b41

I agree with Sam that anything that makes things easier is a good idea; but there's some things that give me pause with this approach.

1) We never give wsgi.server anything besides NullLogger, and all of our logging actually happens at a different level.  It think it's counter intuitive for tests to borrow a logging mechanism that we explicitly bypass everywhere else.  The resulting lines wouldn't ever match anything you'd be likely to see if you actually ran the code. 

2) the signature if the write method on the DebugLogger seems wrong to me, please see comment inline.

I've been looking at this patch for awhile, and it has really got me thinking.  I believe a better approach would be to work towards unifying how we mock logging across the unittest suite.  Maybe something like this would strike you as a better fit for your goals, or if not you could provide feedback how I could make it better:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/57049/"}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-11-18 21:50:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Abandoned

Abandoning in favor of Clay Gerrard's work at: https://review.openstack.org/57049"}]
commit_message:
Use DebugLogger for WSGI servers in unit tests

By using a simple logger that prints stuff to stdout when WSGI
logging is invoked we can more easily debug what request in a
sequence actually encountered the problem.

For example, the output below would be displayed on a failing
test where two of the container servers failed on a PUT:

commit_message:
Pass baremetal-interface to defined XML

In the configure-vm script we allow a baremetal-interface to be defined
but we were not passing this to the XML that's created for the VM. Fixing
this.

Change-Id: Id54106c34816804c7f953e2d41e782ab838a200a

commit_message:
Rename device_driver in neutron::agents::lbaas

Since the havana release, the device_driver parameter for the HAProxy reference
implementation has been changed to
'neutron.services.loadbalancer.drivers.haproxy.namespace_driver.HaproxyNSDriver'.

Upstream reference:

https://github.com/openstack/neutron/commit/358975281f7d9ef43f16febaf27f8f5d1d568426

Do not backport this change into grizzly.

Change-Id: I22369e4875377fe7ac2aa6dd8ea80e04758acbed

commit_message:
Rename device_driver in neutron::agents::lbaas

Since the havana release, the device_driver parameter for the HAProxy reference
implementation has been changed to
'neutron.services.loadbalancer.drivers.haproxy.namespace_driver.HaproxyNSDriver'.

Upstream reference:

https://github.com/openstack/neutron/commit/358975281f7d9ef43f16febaf27f8f5d1d568426

Do not backport this change into grizzly.

Change-Id: I22369e4875377fe7ac2aa6dd8ea80e04758acbed

commit_message:
Also catch UnexpectedTaskStateError_Remote

When an error is passed over RPC it gets the word _Remote appended to
the name, so for any exceptions we are getting back from conductor we
should be checking for the exception and exception_Remote.

This is the first of several patches to make sure _Remote exceptions are
also caught.

This is in an attempt to remove the stacktraces about
UnexpectedTaskStateError in nova-compute.

Change-Id: Ide411b86c09b010de35861e27e9bb388599eb3d1

commit_message:
setting correct configuration file

The metering_secret in the section publisher_rpc should be set
in /etc/ceilometer/ceilometer.conf and not in
/etc/keystone/keystone.conf.

backport: havana

Change-Id: Idb92b94599def85452da6397aaa056d2363667e7

commit_message:
Add troubleshooting override to deploy ramdisk.

We now allow operators to drop into a troubleshooting shell while
booting a deploy ramdisk, without having to have pre-configured their
desire to do so ahead of time, by means of a 10 second pause for them to
press a key.

Change-Id: I05ffa1ebaa95c83dee7bd2a2f52ba4c08928bb10

commit_message:
Fix remove_warnings

Method lib/puppet/provider/keystone.rb/self.remove_providers does not
support multi line warnings and client results having more than one
column. This patch is fixing it (not sure how module can work with such
bug before anyway).

Change-Id: I19c3ce68ef786a2641d1e2808cb4db9979bdcfed

commit_message:
Fix tests in contrib

Add an expected mock call to prevent the tests from going into an
infinite loop.

Shorten the `name` of the test cloud server.  The name was being truncated and
mox was not recognizing the method call.

Change-Id: If927e61ce6f96b5a701e512f7a9054a7ec514967
Closes-Bug: 1251379

commit_message:
use new package name to replace python-pyparsing

on rhels6.4/centos/fedora, there is pyparsing instead of python-pyparsing.
So modify the neutron_python_packages default list. And add one special
case for suse. I also move the messagebus for redhat/centos in the case
statement.

Change-Id: If48d5a35c227223114ac23d5add83d2684a8b717
Closes-Bug: #1244559

commit_message:
Update notifications towards oslo.messaging

* Send notifications upon faults
* Change to a api that emulatse oslo.messagings notification api
* Remove utils.notify

Change-Id: I9499049eebdd571890cd9f11a9fc47eda75d2e45
Signed-off-by: Endre Karlson <endre.karlson@gmail.com>

'}, {'account_id': 8736, 'date': '2013-11-08 17:09:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I wanted to get this out there with only network CRUD before implementing everything in Neutron.  Just want some feedback on my approach before moving forward.'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2013-11-09 03:03:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

A couple of things to keep in mind:
- follow the existing patterns closely
- don't use project names except when necessary, use the API names instead
- I want all of the commands worked out in https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/OpenStackClient/Commands before we implement them in order to keep track of the mapping of the project CLI commands (if applicable) and to track object names in one place
- don't add empty classes just for the sake of adding them; add them as they are implemented.  this keeps from giving users the false impression that commands are available when they are not.
- rebase this against master, right now it depends on an abandoned patch

I really do want to at least map out the network object names as there may be conflicts with other APIs and we should find out now if possible."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-11-16 06:03:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

commit_message:
Removes unnecessary api-paste.ini configuration

Paremeter api_paste_config defaults to '/etc/nova/api-paste.ini',
so it is not needed to set it in nova.conf. Without having
the parameter in nova.conf we can use this module together
with dist.conf. Also filter:authtoken parameters should be
in nova.conf and not in api-paste.ini. Removes filter:authtoken
configuration from api-paste.ini in case it is filled there.

Change-Id: I4798124b3c75c012653c9868c771146f23cf4cc7

commit_message:
Add TOCI_OVERCLOUD_ALL_IN_ONE option.

Adds a new option to support testing with an all-in-one
overcloud template. When the option is used only a single
overcloud image gets built which contains everything.

This will require a new heat template which is added here:

  https://review.openstack.org/56468

Change-Id: I455fd03e9181dcf5f4ea683d1b2fb8435002fb89

commit_message:
Switch to testr / testtools / fixtures, remove nose

* This also fixes us up to hacking standards
* Remove assertGreater* usage in favor of assertEqual py26..
* assertEquals > assertEqual

Change-Id: I8083c96da09897d650ca6fffc0e340d9c057db8d

commit_message:
Added admonition about .ini files

In Heat and Nova sections, where it is recommended to edit an .ini
file, added an admonition about using .ini files general configuration
tasks.

backport: havana

Make the RabbitMQ settings more consistent

Modify the RabbitMQ password for all distributions using it, and provide
configuration informations for all the OpenStack services connected to
the message bus.

backport: havana

(cherry picked from commit d9417b25d97b5acf943575ac74487205ab2f08c1)

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-17 20:51:40.000000000', 'message': 'Split network bringup out of base ramdisk init.

We now run the network bringup portion of the ramdisk init from an
init.d script, thus allowing image builders to inject code into the init
script before that point (e.g. configure network hardware).
The environment variables used by the network bringup code are retained
in the base init script so they can be overridden by init.d fragments.

Change-Id: I1ef0bb21e7f26c0ff3f02266f853ce5402bcb94d
Closes-Bug: #1252023
'}]
commit_message:
Split network bringup out of base ramdisk init.

We now run the network bringup portion of the ramdisk init from an
init.d script, thus allowing image builders to inject code into the init
script before that point (e.g. configure network hardware).
The environment variables used by the network bringup code are retained
in the base init script so they can be overridden by init.d fragments.

Change-Id: I1ef0bb21e7f26c0ff3f02266f853ce5402bcb94d
Closes-Bug: #1252023

commit_message:
Add a pre-deployment check for volume group allocation

If the default disk allocator doesn't allocate enough space
for all volume groups an error will be raised prior to deployment.

Change-Id: Ie6a971ef000ecf9e9b62f137969d05c119e17af6
Closes-Bug: #1248662

commit_message:
Add test for environment deletion

Close issue: PRD-2152

Delete existing environment and verify nodes returns to unallocated state

Scenario:
1. Revert snapshot deploy_simple_flat
2. Delete environment
3. Verify node returns to unallocated pull

Change-Id: I5231eb064ec76ec47c01ef9b57efbee3a0f8a2ca

commit_message:
Absence of conf template issue

Reasons:
taskmanager fails when there is no
available configuration template at trove/templates,
but it should not, because configuration template is optional.

Changes:
covering config rendering with try-finall which would handle error
and would log that excetion if it so,
but that error would not stop provisioning.

Change-Id: Ic0fc87498f0eeec08c1365690ad044b91a28d5af
Fixes: bug #1244665

commit_message:
allow keeping of existing loggers with fileConfig

Currently, common.log.py setup() will disable all existing
loggers that were set up before importing a custom logging
configuration from file. This patch deprecates option name
'log-config' in favor of 'log-config-append' and makes
disable_existing_loggers with default value False.

Closes-Bug: #1169328
Closes-Bug: #1238349
DocImpact

Change-Id: I1f25300d44b04ca5bcdd9b505319f0d089a9c964
(cherry picked from commit 5fef5a8105a85dd8ac07153c48f991fee9726260)

commit_message:
disable/enable host will be failed when using XenServer

When disable/enable host with XenServer, the api of set_host_enabled()
in XenServer driver needs to get service info for the target host, but
the rpc call of set_host_enabled() did not transfer target host as
parameter, this will cause the api call failed.

This patch was transfer host as parameter for the rpc call of
set_host_enabled.

Change-Id: I1aa20414f269bb1a1b81a97c673988c578973367
Closes-Bug: #1251943

[{'account_id': 1812, 'date': '2013-11-18 09:31:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

You should reference the hack

Note there never was a 0.7.3 release.
You should probably have >= 0.8.2 to be less confusing

Note we probably only want to bump this requirement,
when we also remove the sqlalchemy <= 0.7.99 cap?"}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2013-11-18 10:10:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> You should reference the hack

Not really handy to reference something like that in a commit message unless I reference some external link.

https://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/ceilometer/tree/ceilometer/storage/sqlalchemy/migration.py#n51


> Note there never was a 0.7.3 release. You should probably have >= 0.8.2 to be less confusing

It's a logical dependency, I don't care about what really existed.

> Note we probably only want to bump this requirement, when we also remove the sqlalchemy <= 0.7.99 cap?

Not sure, 0.8.2 is already pulled already."}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2013-11-18 10:10:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

Abandoning for https://review.openstack.org/#/c/56662/'}]

commit_message:
Bump sqlalchemy-migrate to 0.7.3

This will allow a lot of OpenStack project to remove a dirty hack that
is not needed anymore with 0.7.3.

Change-Id: I3320fde7b933a497b14954e5f2d548ec91b4bbf9

commit_message:
Adding qpid support to quantum

Moving all qpid parameters under default["openstack"]["network"]["mq"]["qpid"]
so that other qpid options can be added under it. Rabbit parameters
will be brought under "mq" eventually.

Change-Id: I581ecc5304ec61b285362a62602fc7a11e18cd3e
Implements: blueprint qpid-activemq-support

commit_message:
/bin/bash all the things.

Since we are using bash syntax in some of the element fragments,
we should make sure we use bash for all of them, so that things don't
break on systems where /bin/sh != /bin/bash.

Change-Id: If2f043c57aa4e1492b7f9839213ef6123f683612

commit_message:
Don't block the upstart daemon if it doesn't exist

Check if Upstart exists before blocking the daemon.  Not all dpkg based
OS's have Upstart installed so this should help increase compatibility.

Closes-Bug: #1251949
Change-Id: I2dcb1ff3641778b5653ca5762a728398adb57da1

[{'created': '2013-11-16 22:30:18.000000000', 'message': 'Make pxe_mac accurate in two common cases.

If we are booting pxe booting using syslinux, and it has IPAPPEND 2 in
the boot stanza, then it will append the mac address of the device we
are booting from to the kernel parameters where we can get at it
pretty easily.

If we are booting physical hardware via UEFI over the network, we can
rely on the BootCurrent EFI variable to point at the boot entry for
the NIC we booted from, which will include the MAC address of that
nic.

If neither of those cases are in play, we can jsut fall back to the
first-physical-device-with-a-link code.

This currently uses the Bash 4 support for associative arrays to handle
the netboot-in-UEFI case, if needed I can rewrite it to be Bash 3 compatible.

Change-Id: I5e50e30c60d6d732a09ab61251cbb9be08bb6113
'}, {'created': '2013-11-18 03:46:50.000000000', 'message': 'Make pxe_mac accurate in two common cases.

If we are booting pxe booting using syslinux, and it has IPAPPEND 2 in
the boot stanza, then it will append the mac address of the device we

'}]
commit_message:
Make pxe_mac accurate in two common cases.

If we are booting pxe booting using syslinux, and it has IPAPPEND 2 in
the boot stanza, then it will append the mac address of the device we
are booting from to the kernel parameters where we can get at it
pretty easily.

If we are booting physical hardware via UEFI over the network, we can
rely on the BootCurrent EFI variable to point at the boot entry for
the NIC we booted from, which will include the MAC address of that
nic.

If neither of those cases are in play, we can just fall back to the
all-physical-devices-with-links code.

This currently uses the Bash 4 support for associative arrays to handle
the netboot-in-UEFI case, if needed I can rewrite it to be Bash 3 compatible.

Change-Id: I5e50e30c60d6d732a09ab61251cbb9be08bb6113

commit_message:
Use DIB_INIT_SYSTEM for systemd checks.

Minor additions to b01c73a where we switched over to use
DIB_INIT_SYSTEM instead of a systemd file check.

This commit updates a couple remaining Fedora distro checks to use
to use the dib init system check instead.

Change-Id: Ifc1ed73b23827005cbdba3531e113491f734c9af

commit_message:
Added to release branches to build

By adding release-x.x branches to build job, we ensure that
all documentation, including from not yet released versions are
going to be built.

To add new release or release branch to build - add new tag or
branch to 'version' variable.

Change-Id: Ib43b5dd6845f2c7337cdee04dafc2d400ca08e73

commit_message:
Add Quota middlewares support

Two middlewares exist for managing quotas:
- account_quotas
- container_quotas

Change-Id: Ic6d539db480d8749769279b44e1f38302ac0fa62
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

commit_message:
hyperv: Initialize target_iqn in attach_volume

The target_iqn is referenced before it is declared in the
case that an exception is encountered in _login_storage_target
or _get_mounted_disk_from_lun.  This causes the exception path
to cause an additional, misleading, traceback to be printed
after an exception is encountered.

This commit initializes target_iqn at the beginning of
attach_volume to avoid the traceback.

Closes-Bug: 1233837
Change-Id: I1cdfb9dfa054ee4f4f6918d7bc49081ccaebab9d
(cherry picked from commit 9baa186ebb578205c513c94fc621e254f4c13a08)

[{'created': '2013-10-29 22:31:46.000000000', 'message': "Cells: Fix instance deletes

A regression was introduced with object conversion that caused all
instances to be locally deleted in the API cell when cells is enabled.
This would happen before the child cell was told to delete the instance.

Additionally, if an instance record was created in a child cell but
failed to schedule to a host in such a way that the API cell has
no knowledge of the 'host', the instance would be deleted in the API
cell only.

Also, it appears that we would cast deletes to child cells twice due to
logic duplicated in cells_api.py that exists in api.py.

"}]
commit_message:
Cells: Fix instance deletes

A regression was introduced with object conversion that caused all
instances to be locally deleted in the API cell when cells is enabled.
This would happen before the child cell was told to delete the instance.

Additionally, if an instance record was created in a child cell but
failed to schedule to a host in such a way that the API cell has
no knowledge of the 'host', the instance would be deleted in the API
cell only.

Also, it appears that we would cast deletes to child cells twice due to
logic duplicated in cells_api.py that exists in api.py.

Closes-Bug: #1240247

Change-Id: I94cfddd9cef2d63b2cb31c0f2dae8e211a4418d9
(cherry picked from commit 0493c803ae9612f87ed028e1a39e880aead5bdcb)

commit_message:
Introduce storage.object.* metrics

New metrics:

   storage.object.upload
   storage.object.download
   storage.object.update
   storage.object.delete

Every of this metric is suffixed with 'internal' or 'external',
distinguishing internal and external users. User considered internal
if an IP address from his request belongs to 'internal_subnet', which
is defined in the config file.

Change-Id: I84b298d1e326d2b8ab1578f56658f2803e9adbf2

commit_message:
Change negative smoke test to gate tests

Negative tests are often no real somke tests. Together with
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/51590/ this will correct all wrongly
tagged tests and move these negative tests into seperate files.

Change-Id: I6f1786e1f1e3670226a1eca3e15fe21581f351b0

commit_message:
Fixes Invalid tag name error when using k:v tagname

This patch fixes the invalid tag name error when k:v type
tagname appears in response of api during xml serialization,
the tagname which contains colon couldn't be supported by
default since it is reserved by xml namespace, this patch
solve it by adding the k of k:v tagname into namespace.

Fixes bug: #1213927

Change-Id: Ib20efb378425cbe5deef45fbac561955cbe0f7bc
(cherry picked from commit 80b11279ba9853a9ab743ec6987c3229fff0b5e4)

commit_message:
Add _() to fix i18N compliance (part 2)

In heat, almost 200 log message and at least 30 exception
message are not processed by _(), and will not been translated.
We should use '_("STRING ...")' to enable i18n support.

I split to two parts for review easier because the files
lost of _() are too much.

Change-Id: I36ccd119fc1dcb58e98b77b2c9d139af6a380a7a
Closes-Bug: #1249217

commit_message:
Do not run "ovs-ofctl add-flow" with an invalid in_port

Since ofport is a string, we have to convert it to integer to
check it expresses a negative number or not.

Also unit tests are added/corrected.

Change-Id: If85595f1b8ecb40ea41edda52706fb1bd41cb1ab
Related-Bug: 1238445

Thanks Dan, please check my answers in line.'}, {'account_id': 7494, 'date': '2013-10-31 07:26:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Dan, I want to give more explanation for how does _create_image when revert resize a VM.

1) For a non LVM image, by default, the image will be stored at /opt/stack/data/nova/instances/uuid/ (installed by devstack), when revert resize a VM instance, libvirt driver will first destroy the resized VM, this will destroy the image of the VM. Then libvirt driver will rename the file /opt/stack/data/nova/instances/uuid_resize to /opt/stack/data/nova/instances/uuid, and as the VM image was also under /opt/stack/data/nova/instances/uuid, so _create_image will detect that the image was already there and it will not create image any more.
2) For a LVM based image, when revert resize a VM, after the VM destroyed, the VM LVM image was also destroyed. As for a LVM based VM, the image was not under /opt/stack/data/nova/instances/uuid, so we need recreate the LVM image for such case.'}, {'account_id': 7494, 'date': '2013-10-31 07:38:33.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-31 08:12:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Works for me

commit_message:
Create image again when resize revert a VM with image type as LVM

When resize revert a VM, the original image will be deleted. But
for LVM based VM, the image was not re-created after the for this
case, and this will cause resize revert failed.

The fix was add _create_image() logic before define the VM in
finish_revert_migration to make sure define VM can always find
a image file of the VM.

_create_image() was an exist call in libvirt driver, the logic was
if the VM image already exists, just return and use the existed
image; If the image does not exist, create a new image for the VM.

Change-Id: I39c95400bf813fe4ce4490731832a83701848dc7
Closes-Bug: #1242233

commit_message:
move test_instance_actions.py to admin dir

Move the file tempest/api/compute/servers/test_instance_actions.py to the
admin test directory because the admin priviledge is needed. The default
policy of 'instance_actions:events' is admin only, and we need to test
it. I'll add some tests in the next patch, these patches are just splited
according to
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Gerrit_Workflow#Long-lived_Topic_Branches

Change-Id: Ifa212e76b4f1906b4d792094082ee3eb9a3cf4eb

commit_message:
Improves Usability for Default Quotas Tab

The table in the Default Quota Tab has been rearranged to match the Edit
Project dialog in the Quota tab. Some fields are missing since there is
no support for Neutron default quotas yet. The spellings have been fixed
in the current master release.

Partially Fixes Bug : 1210533

Change-Id: Ie8e5955558cad48165bc4c1e4845bcb54e88fa06

commit_message:
Fixes Error when contain Non-ascii in template

when set template use non-english resource_name and execute
"heat -v resource-list $stack_id". KeyError will occur because
heat can not encode it correctly. This patch will implement
a process to encode the resource_name.

The patch use a new module (strutils.py) taken from
oslo-incubator in order to use safe_encode() and
safe_decode(), and this module is useful for future
patchs.

Change-Id: Idddda20d96bca32cb4df94ede31b40f7141e3afe
Closes-Bug: #1249238

commit_message:
Make instance Tags updatable

Note: I don't think that there is an issue with autoscaling tags
as autoscaling drives the instance via the properties and it doesn't
update intances anyways, it only creates/destroys instances.

Change-Id: I3cea4180f22690ea226273cc96132db6ae3dde12
Closes-bug: #1240885

[{'created': '2013-11-14 18:42:37.000000000', 'message': 'Check only our VG name when testing if VG exists

Rather than calling "vgs" we should just call
"vgs <cinder-vg-name>" which returns only information about the VG
we are querying.

Also hardens test command string matching to error on unexpected
calls.

Change-Id: I25580e34b6589e161a51274f22dbb9ed922e43ed
'}]
commit_message:
Check only our VG name when testing if VG exists

Rather than calling "vgs" we should just call
"vgs <cinder-vg-name>" which returns only information about the VG
we are querying.

Also hardens test command string matching to error on unexpected
calls.

Change-Id: I25580e34b6589e161a51274f22dbb9ed922e43ed

commit_message:
Improve the api versioning

- Don't use the project version for the API, but
  the actual API version (just v1 defined now).
- Change the return type to a list of versions (we can't be
  that optimistic).

blueprint api
Change-Id: Icb8c0c91798cf4eb1e10b39040e123119e859d10

commit_message:
Allow nova metadata to be updated

Note this is metadata not Metadata (confusing, I know).

This does not need to be run in a task as the server does not
change state for metadata changes.

Change-Id: If5f9ee89984fab388c0c9d839fbe23a59c68046b
Closes-bug: #1250638

Overall I don't really like this, it seems very dangerous to be masking all neutron client exceptions when trying to get the security groups. Even if you scope the exception handling to only 404s, it still seems bad. I read that the neutron guys don't think this should be done differently in the client, but I might argue that the neutron client/server could raise a different, more specific exception in the NoopFirewallDriver case so that the client can provide a specific exception and then nova can simply handle that isolated case.

I've seen a lot of patches in nova that are trying to handle exceptions from neutronclient in an intelligent way but most of the time they fail because the exceptions coming from the neutronclient are for the most part ambiguous."}, {'account_id': 6722, 'date': '2013-11-05 02:24:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Matt,

I agree with you that neutron client needs raise specific exception for different situation.

I would like hold this until fix from neturon client."}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2013-11-11 16:33:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

I think there are several ways to address this problem:

(a) Nova checks if neutron secuirty-group is enabled. it can be done by checking security-group is included in enable extension list (which can be retrieved via Neutron API). Nova can distinguish a case where Neutron security-group is enabled from NotFound exception by doing so.

(b) To change neutron behavior with iptables-based agent security group impl (such as OVS plugin) and make neutron security-group enabled even if NoopFirewallDriver is used. In this case Neutron actually does not provide security group feature but security group API behaves as if it is enabled. I am afraid It may be confusing.

When Neutron (Quantum) security group was implemented, nova security group is commonly used and we neutron community thought the behavior (b) looks good. However, considering a situation where neutron becomes the default network impl, this behavior might not be appropriate and it may be a good chance to change it. Once neutron becomes the only impl of openstack network and security group becomes core API, we need a way to disable security group and NoopFirewallDriver is a good way to do so.

I am open to the discussion of the future of the behavior of neutron OVS security group.
We tried to start the discussion in the dev ML, but unfortunately only few folks were interested in the topic....'}, {'account_id': 2711, 'date': '2013-11-13 08:44:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

The command nova list/show is not working if setting NoopFirewallDriver
as firewall in Neutron, since the extension of security groups won't
be loaded by Neutron, which leads an exception raised by neutronclient.

This patch check if security_group is enabled. If not, just return an
empty security_group.

Closes-Bug: #1232965

commit_message:
Fix operation failure with NoopFirewallDriver

The command nova list/show is not working if setting NoopFirewallDriver
as firewall in Neutron, since the extension of security groups won't
be loaded by Neutron, which leads an exception raised by neutronclient.

This patch check if security_group is enabled. If not, just return an
empty security_group.

Closes-Bug: #1232965

Change-Id: I0c5032040f40518eebcdd78ebc2cc67580e00443

commit_message:
Remove hanging ';' in some os attributes

Some os attributes (2) have a "hanging" semi-colon, probably where
another os value has previously been removed but not the associated
divider.

I've removed these as a prelude to an additional check I wish
to add to tools/test.py to pick up unknown os values.

Change-Id: I469ea81f5a48f762cd0f6f2e92d457416360976e
backport: havana
(cherry picked from commit acc8142da50f340a58e780318167505bf001f7f7)

commit_message:
Switch novato the upstream api-paste.ini

We had a copy of this file which needed to be maintained by tripleo,
using the upstream version means we should no longer have to maintain
it. In this case the reason for doing this is to enable the nova v3 API.

The tempest tests for the nova v3 api require it to be enabled.

Change-Id: I98583009cd18adda4443ce0b00a584434a4abf81

commit_message:
Remove hanging ';' in some os attributes

Some os attributes (2) have a "hanging" semi-colon, probably where
another os value has previously been removed but not the associated
divider.

I've removed these as a prelude to an additional check I wish
to add to tools/test.py to pick up unknown os values.

Change-Id: I469ea81f5a48f762cd0f6f2e92d457416360976e
backport: havana

Corrected cases where conflicting profiling values excluded content
entirely from some guides. The majority of these changes were cases
where a parent node listed all os values *except* Debian yet a child
node for Debian was present.

This resulted in the relevant sections being ommitted entirely from the
Debian version of the guide.

Change-Id: Ia5df52e81e937e9b568779b6f5cc1645f6564d62
backport: havana

'}]
commit_message:
Fix cases where conflicting profiling excluded content

Corrected cases where conflicting profiling values excluded content
entirely from some guides. The majority of these changes were cases
where a parent node listed all os values *except* Debian yet a child
node for Debian was present.

This resulted in the relevant sections being ommitted entirely from the
Debian version of the guide.

Change-Id: Ia5df52e81e937e9b568779b6f5cc1645f6564d62
backport: havana
(cherry picked from commit 4bc5ca0712008824b4a35ea5cd2ca2425c5d8b4c)

commit_message:
Add special serial smoke option

We want smoketests to be parallel by default (for grenade etc), but that won't work
for neutron, so add a special case. Since we don't want to break
anything making this switch, it has to be done in 3 steps:

1) this patch
2) make neutron use smoke-serial
3) change smoke to be parallel

Note this is a backport to grizzly so the parallel options are not being
added, we are just maintaining serialized testing on the grizzly branch.

Change-Id: I03ded120c0b496026e39f14f6715624a91ac7558

commit_message:
Add special serial smoke option

We want smoketests to be parallel by default (for grenade etc), but that won't work
for neutron, so add a special case. Since we don't want to break
anything making this switch, it has to be done in 3 steps:

1) this patch
2) make neutron use smoke-serial
3) change smoke to be parallel

Change-Id: I03ded120c0b496026e39f14f6715624a91ac7558

[{'created': '2013-11-14 04:22:03.000000000', 'message': "Round-robin SVI switch selection fails on Cisco Nexus plugin

Fixes bug 1250969

This fix addresses improper behavior with the Cisco Nexus plugin's
selection of Nexus switch on which to place a Switch Virtual Interface
(SVI) when round-robin switch placement is enabled.

The expected behavior when round-robin SVI switch selection is configured
via the cisco_plugins.ini file, i.e.:
    [cisco]
    nexus_l3_enable = True
    svi_round_robin = True
is that when a virtual router interface is created, the Nexus plugin should
select the Nexus switch with the least number of SVI interfaces configured
for creating the new SVI. The current selection is based on the first
entry in a dictionary, and is therefore indeterminate.

Similarly, this fix also addresses incorrect behavior when round-robin
selection is disabled. In this case, the desired behavior is that
the plugin should select the first switch which appears in the Nexus
switch configuration. Instead, the current selection is also based on the
first entry in a dictionary, and is likewise indeterminate.

Change-Id: I548c1efaa8b54695246251b6823ab59e077836fe

commit_message:
Round-robin SVI switch selection fails on Cisco Nexus plugin

Fixes bug 1250969

This fix addresses improper behavior with the Cisco Nexus plugin's
selection of Nexus switch on which to place a Switch Virtual Interface
(SVI) when round-robin switch placement is enabled.

The expected behavior when round-robin SVI switch selection is configured
via the cisco_plugins.ini file, i.e.:
    [cisco]
    nexus_l3_enable = True
    svi_round_robin = True
is that when a virtual router interface is created, the Nexus plugin should
select the Nexus switch with the least number of SVI interfaces configured
for creating the new SVI. The current selection is based on the first
entry in a dictionary, and is therefore indeterminate.

Similarly, this fix also addresses incorrect behavior when round-robin
selection is disabled. In this case, the desired behavior is that
the plugin should select the first switch which appears in the Nexus
switch configuration. Instead, the current selection is also based on the
first entry in a dictionary, and is likewise indeterminate.

Change-Id: I548c1efaa8b54695246251b6823ab59e077836fe

commit_message:
Removes unused nvp plugin config param

nvp_cluster_uuid is no longer used; it was missed
during the configuration file tweaks that was done
during Havana.

Change-Id: Id6dd684833c99453cd97d88584be04d99fd21550
Closes-bug: #1251086

commit_message:
python3: Fix print statements

Fix print statements while running with python3. This is
due to the fact that the print() has changed between
python2 and python3.

Change-Id: I36831ca0e398c611e76cef38439adee37ed6d50e
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>

commit_message:
Enable all nova v3 tests

To merge a nova v3 patch (I452672e064d0dc4a1d5700bb96c01de8087f33d8),
all nova v3 tests have been skipped because the patch changes common
parameter("admin_password") of nova v3 API.
After merging the patch, we need to enable all nova v3 tests again with
changing the API parameter.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests
Change-Id: Ia5b3bd123a20196fd15bbb6771b6cf929121532a

commit_message:
Add log statements for policy check failures

Misconfiguration of the policy.json file may
cause policy check failures. It's kind to the
developer to log the underlying exception
so that he/she can have more information as to
how to address the problem.

Closes bug: #1246139

Change-Id: I8664959cb98b3a41d159db3acb91da9baba810ae

commit_message:
Detect conflicting profiling attributes

Detect situations where content is accidentally excluded from the build
because the os profiling of one element contradicts that of its
children. For example:

<itemisedlist os="opensuse;sles">
  <listitem os="ubuntu;debian">

The listitem in this example can never be displayed as the os conditions
it specifies are not a subset of those specified by its parent.

Change-Id: I17fb2e249210052d3c166d85533f72fa491f955c

commit_message:
Fix cases where conflicting profiling excluded content

Corrected cases where conflicting profiling values excluded content
entirely from some guides. The majority of these changes were cases
where a parent node listed all os values *except* Debian yet a child
node for Debian was present.

This resulted in the relevant sections being ommitted entirely from the
Debian version of the guide.

Change-Id: Ia5df52e81e937e9b568779b6f5cc1645f6564d62
backport: havana

As of Python 2.6, BaseException.message is deprecated, so just pass the

commit_message:
Stop using BaseException.message when re-raising

As of Python 2.6, BaseException.message is deprecated, so just pass the
exception itself into the exception we raise.

Change-Id: Ib9c0e62d7b5049b53a8ab28079984d7329f976ca

commit_message:
Add wheel mirror structure awareness

We are going to start having wheels in the gate. Having them there
should not break folks who are not using wheels.  Don't start actually
consuming wheels yet, but add awareness about the wheel structure to the
pypi config.

Change-Id: Id29bb1bb31fc1647f8e1ea00bab487e447ba2838

commit_message:
Remove pip as an argument from mkvenv

We no longer care about or support old pip, because it turns out that
evil happens. Remove it from the mkvenv function.

Change-Id: I27dbef7816eaac856e97ec5a036f6d5ca9b183af

At any rate, your change is still missing a test."}, {'account_id': 6624, 'date': '2013-11-07 10:47:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

So, there are two things here, I guess:

1) Whether the template store should be read only
2) Where the correct data is currently stored.

I don't care one way or the other about the first one, although I'm inclined towards thinking it should be read only, as a user requesting the template for the stack should get back the template they uploaded (principle of least surprise and all that).

Currently, the template is not updated during autoscaling.InstanceGroup._lb_reload() or neutron.loadblancer.LoadBalancer.handle_update(), but handle_update() does update the ResourceData mappings.  Since this is the case, it makes sense to me to look at ResourceData mappings on update - it's of course correct to look at the template during handle_create.

I am working my way through unmocking enough of the test case to expose the original bug so that I can prove my change fixes it :)"}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-11-11 11:09:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I don't think this is the right solution because it creates a fourth inconsistent copy of the same data (the template, scaling group resource, Neutron, and now the LB resource).

IMO we shouldn't be relying on the diff to figure out what changes to make. We should be attempting to end up in the state where the list in Neutron is exactly the list passed. That implies we need to compare against the current state in Neutron, not against any other previous state we might have locally."}, {'account_id': 6624, 'date': '2013-11-11 12:02:30.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 6624, 'date': '2013-11-11 12:10:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

So, this slightly long test case finally proves that there is a bug that needs addressing.  I'm happy to do it by looking at the ResourceData cache for the ELB, and I'm happy to do it by looking at neutron.  Looking at the local cache seems simpler, and less like redo'ing work, but I don't really mind either way.  Let me know which to implement.

Cheers,"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-11 12:35:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Doesn't seem to work

[{'created': '2013-11-05 20:59:46.000000000', 'message': "Get pool members from DB API

When the Load Balancer members are created as a result of autoscaling
groups calling _lb_update, the reference to the current members is
stored in the database and not in the template.  Retrieve the list from
there if the list in the template is empty.

Arguably, this is what should always be done, since the database should
be reflecting the 'last known good' state of things, rather than the
state that things started with.

Closes-Bug: #1248218
Change-Id: Iaf8097eff6ad5ae0809d56604699dca2b08db3f4
Signed-off-by: Stephen Gran <stephen.gran@guardian.co.uk>

commit_message:
Get pool members from DB API

When the Load Balancer members are created as a result of autoscaling
groups calling _lb_update, the reference to the current members is
stored in the database and not in the template.  Treat ResourceData
mappings as canonical.

Closes-Bug: #1248218
Change-Id: Iaf8097eff6ad5ae0809d56604699dca2b08db3f4

commit_message:
Remove reduntant call to update_instance_info_cache

get_instance_nw_info calls _get_instance_nw_info,
which is decorated with @refresh_cache. This in
turn calls update_instance_info_cache, again. This
is both expensive and more importantly dangerous because
the method update_instance_info_cache may call
_get_instance_nw_info itself, thus causing an infinite
loop.

Change-Id: Id8f0241d1c6609cf4e064ee6855228ae7de250e2
Partial-bug: 1235435

commit_message:
Use cached volumes in REST API extensions

This patch caches db volumes in the core volumes API so that they can be
used in the host and tenant attribute API extensions in order to lower
the response time by avoiding costly individual db queries for each
volume in the REST API contributions.

Change-Id: Ie0cbe929379df32fddbdce1953f13b6f26208bff
Partial-Bug: #1197612

commit_message:
Enable object caching in cinder REST API requests

Allow the core API to cache resources, such as DB results, so that
extensions can use data already retrieved within the same API request
eliminating additional expensive DB calls.

Loosely based on commit 9f9fbc54e7336da10fc3056bdaca2ec7d01c7f94 from
nova.

Change-Id: If9f49faf7305287c0489ad6209cf19b8bec612cc
Partial-Bug: #1197612

commit_message:
Make the RabbitMQ settings more consistent

Modify the RabbitMQ password for all distributions using it, and provide
configuration informations for all the OpenStack services connected to
the message bus.

Change-Id: I6309c9080ab34885c68c11b5d37783e07bdd98bd
backport: havana
Closes-Bug: #1249230

commit_message:
Lower severity of log trace for DB integrity error

LOG.exception is not appropriate, since a concurrent
port creation can occur and it has been dealt with
in the except block.

This avoids spooking users who are on the hunt for
real bugs.

Supports fix for 1239637

Change-Id: I9489702ee63db0b004fe41195fa4727af261d514

commit_message:
Use dib helper script to determine init system

diskimage-builder provides a helper script + env variable
to determine, which init system is used. We should use them
in elements instead of manual checks after update of raring
cloud images broke "if [ -d /etc/systemd/system ]" test.

Related-Bug: #1251610

Change-Id: I6d27491302ff0c4c6de82d6d60fc80e83fec519e

Elements form a set. We don't support (and don't want to from a complexity perspective) support replacing part of an element: if you need to replace the contents of an element, replace the entire element. This avoids creating untested permutations.

I'm open to the idea that we may need to revisit this - but there needs to be broad discussion - perhaps a bug and/or etherpad would be a suitable way to get discussion on this?"}, {'account_id': 1991, 'date': '2013-11-16 03:08:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Preserve element ordering

When dependent elements are caculated, preserve the user specified
ordering of the elements.  This allows a user to possibly override a
hook from a previous element.

Change-Id: I9bf39d0f3eebfcd4989f56d2e035e9610722db46

commit_message:
python3: Work around httpretty issue

Currently running tox.ini with py33 installation
fails because of a failure to read a unicode file
while installing httpretty.

Closes-Bug: #1241560

Change-Id: I6012c4fcca0d0354f0c1bdf4797f6e7409f7bf1c
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>

commit_message:
Misc Minor Fixes for Storage Policies

- fixed issue in proxy container POST similar to recent PUT fix (if condition not correct for INT)
- coorected a few test cases using PUT instead of POST
- added missing test for convert_policy_to_index in ContainerController
- added test to provide coverage for maksing sure policy is correctly added to back end headers
(adds coverage for recent if INT condition issues in container PUT/POST for policy 0)

Change-Id: Ifcdf26321491ed2455bbc03636e4b1b318b7d299
Implements: blueprint swift-ec

commit_message:
Supporting both Python 2 and Python 3 with six

We should use six.text_type for both python2 and python3 for
textual data type, not unicode, it supports python 2 only.

Change-Id: Ia5d7b5df83ff1a7536954f6a190502f117c80ff2
Partial-Bug: #1249886

commit_message:
Adds new/merge rate to reviewers information

Adds more per day stats:
  - Changes with at least one patchset active in the time period
  - New changes uploaded
  - Changes merged
  - Changes abandoned
  - Changes left in WIP
Estimation of queue growth based over the time period

commit_message:
Make sorting of ramdisk init elements explicit.

We assemble the init script of ramdisks with the fragments from included
elements, alphabetically.
We now place leading numbers on all of the fragments we ship, to make it
more obvious to element authors and downstream users, how the process
works.

Closes-Bug: #1251706

Change-Id: I56b0d42971c8c462eddcfe1769f8124405e1233c

commit_message:
Register API options under the 'api' group

Register the API options under the 'api' group and change the name of
the options to be less redundant.

This patch also regenerates the sample config file.

Change-Id: I55ec0b977275a394fef059a6318540bb5186ddc0
Closes-Bug: #1244742

[{'created': '2013-11-12 09:38:21.000000000', 'message': 'Don't install novnc from package by default

By default the installation is failed because the novnc package has got
the a dependency of the nova-common package. The last package provides
"/etc/nova/*" files with appropriate privileges. It potentially brings
to the problem of an access to those files.

Change-Id: I1689bef817365b10bf972dc4a8033892ad5939d1
Related-Bug: 1248923
'}]
commit_message:
Don't install novnc from package by default

By default the installation is failed because the novnc package has got
the a dependency of the nova-common package. The last package provides
"/etc/nova/*" files with appropriate privileges. It potentially brings
to the problem of an access to those files.

Change-Id: I1689bef817365b10bf972dc4a8033892ad5939d1
Related-Bug: 1248923

commit_message:
Remove sqlalchemy-migrate 0.7.3 patching

Now that sqlalchemy-migrate 0.8.x is available, remove the 0.7.3
patching. This allows environments to pick up 0.8.1 automatically, while
avoiding the version string error. Once an update to global-requirements
is made, another patch will pin our sqlalchemy-migrate version >= 0.8.2.

This is copied from change I5f80dfc07f8256716d025002fc1a1f47e58b2142

Change-Id: I646a5a8f427095e20b09fbf2db796d2644def6fc
Closes-bug: 1251700

commit_message:
Update openstack/common/lockutils

The following commits are in this update:

79e6bc6 fix lockutils.lock() to make it thread-safe
ace5120 Add main() to lockutils that creates temp dir for locks
537d8e2 Allow lockutils to get lock_path conf from envvar

Change-Id: Id50b7c0ccbb417493320e19191a92675fcf126ff

I'm not convinced of the logic here.   From what I can see this will cache an admin token for the life of thread, but threads in nova-compute are long lived and reused to serve multiple requests.  So it looks as if each thread in the rpc event pool (and the periodic task) would get its own admin token - but what happens when those tokens expire ?"}, {'account_id': 5638, 'date': '2013-11-13 11:26:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

recheck no bug'}, {'account_id': 5638, 'date': '2013-11-13 11:28:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

@Phil, great question. In the neutron client, when the tokens expire (for admin scenario), there is enough information to generate a new one. So the neutron client just goes ahead and mints a new one and retries the operation. So we should be good. This was exactly the reasoning behind Drew's previous change to setup the credentials properly for the admin scenario so tokens can be re-genned."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-13 12:11:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

commit_message:
Cache Neutron Client for Admin Scenarios

Store a thread local copy of Neutron client for use with admin
tokens, this will prevent excessive calls to keystone to mint
new tokens and will enable reuse of the already set up client
for subsequent calls in this thread.

Change-Id: I6346281ca3516c31b195ce71942786d724e5e9df
Closes-Bug: #1250580

commit_message:
Sync log module from oslo

This patch sync latest log module from oslo, bases on oslo-incubator
commit f06276bbdabd408549ecefa377b1349b57f5ac82.

DocImpact: Deprecate option log_config in favor of log_config_append.
Change option default_log_levels's default value.

Change-Id: Id2f7cf245499394554f6aa2c8d846cc9e2c2133a

commit_message:
Moved keystone db sync to its own class

This will decouple allowing for additions, like the apache wsgi
patch, so it can be included or triggered elsewhere.

Original author is François Charlier<francois.charlier@enovance.com>

Change-Id: I9ae544d58034ca30ddb0a4c616ff794ccd432d7f

commit_message:
Introduction of ceph installation and configuration management

* ceph is used to do the installation and configuration of
common dependencies across classes (such as ceph package
installation, global configuration namespaces in ceph.conf).

* ceph::params is meant to hold defaults/constants for various
classes and manage operating system differences in the future.

* ceph::osd, ceph::mon, ceph::mds are introduced solely to manage
their respective 'global' configuration for the time being.

It was decided that we leave most default configurations up to Ceph
unless they are necessary in installing the cluster.
As such, the configurations that are probably most likely to be
changed are available as parameters but optional. If they are not
set (undef), the ceph_config provider will not write them to
ceph.conf and thus, Ceph will handle the defaults.

Other configuration options (exotic or otherwise) can always be
set through the users' manifests with the help of ceph_config.
If support is required, we can always add them if necessary.

Change-Id: I0020a65fe1caada8bc46f6dc63254bcfefb64dbb

I'm not entirely convinced that I like the degree of automation that we're aiming for here.   I get the principle of running filters that take out the most hosts first,  but at the moment you can manually configure that by specifying the filter order in the config options - for example we always run the AZ filter first as it can take out 2/3rds of the hosts - but that might not be optimal for all configurations. 

Isn't this just better covered by good documentation suggesting a sample order and explaining that users should tune for their specific system by looking in the log to see how many hosts were removed by each filter ?   

If you really want to automate it then we could save data on each pass on how many hosts each filter eliminated and use that to pick the order for the next run (allowing uses to either have or not have that kind of auto tuning)

This kind of approximation seems to be neither one thing or the other - and takes away a degree of control that some users may want.

(also the BP isn't actually approved yet - but that's a minor point)"}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2013-11-14 19:45:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Good points, Phil.  I didn't think about the fact that you could already sort them to optimize manually, and that this could interfere with that.  Hrm ..."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-11-15 20:39:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I agree with phil"}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2013-11-15 20:47:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Cool, after this feedback, I'm just going to abandon.

Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2013-11-15 20:47:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Add sorting of scheduler host filters

Some filters are known to be more expensive to execute than others.  For
example, there are a number of filters that hit the database for each
host it looks at.  It is advantageous for performance to roughly sort
the filters based on their cost to execute.  The more hosts we can
eliminate using quick local-only filters, the better.

Implements blueprint scheduler-host-filter-sorting

Change-Id: I372fcd206391b561ad102fd62ca9618b5104b676

commit_message:
Pass flow failures to task's revert method

Now when tasks are reverted, all flows failures seen so far are passed
to revert method as 'flow_failures' keyword argument, as a dictionary
task name => misc.Failure.

Closes-bug: #1246616
Change-Id: I81f8c10684d54aaf5c31bb3badb6afe4c949f680

commit_message:
Storage: add methods to get all flow failures

Instead of caching all failures in engine we cache them in storage,
which is cleaner and more transparent.

Behavior change: if task failed, then flow was suspended, then
loaded again but without task with such name, such flow would be
reverted now in engine.run(). Previously, such flow could be run
normally as all data from not present tasks were ignored.

Closes-bug: #1251736
Change-Id: I64e99ca98cc7fd28957ac2468577d677641aebdc

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-16 20:15:48.000000000', 'message': 'Refactor configuring of floating ips on a router.

This approach to configuring floating ips is stateless and idempotent.
This allows it to handle corner cases, such as reusing a floating ip
address with a different floating ip id in a way that is easier to
understand.

The concept is to wipe the floating ips clean and rebuild them each
time with the following optimizations.  To avoid bad performance in
manipulating iptables, it is called in the context of a call to
defer_apply_on.  To avoid a disruption in network flow a set
difference is use to determine the set of addresses that no longer
belong on the inteface rather than removing them all blindly.

Change-Id: I98aacbbb52b35688036990961d02e0b273504a77
Fixes: Bug #1209011

commit_message:
Refactor configuring of floating ips on a router

This approach to configuring floating ips is stateless and idempotent.
This allows it to handle corner cases, such as reusing a floating ip
address with a different floating ip id in a way that is easier to
understand.

The concept is to wipe the floating ips clean and rebuild them each
time with the following optimizations.  To avoid bad performance in
manipulating iptables, it is called in the context of a call to
defer_apply_on.  To avoid a disruption in network flow a set
difference is use to determine the set of addresses that no longer
belong on the inteface rather than removing them all blindly.

Change-Id: I98aacbbb52b35688036990961d02e0b273504a77
Fixes: Bug #1209011
