commit_message:
one global-requirements.txt to rule them all

... and in the darkness bind them.

This moves the contents of requirements.txt and
test-requirements.txt to a single file, global-requirements.txt.
This means that regardless of whether a requirement is in
either file it will get checked. This massively simplifies the
checking and upgrading of req and test-req files.

This also adds in a unit testing framework for the update.py
script to ensure it does what we think it does. This is
accomplished by making a fake tree with a set of req and test-req
files, running update.py, and ensuring the updates were made
that we expected. It includes testing for the oslo url case,
as well as test-requires.

(cherry picked from commit ec9cf616904d92509b8b44662e7097352d894484)
(cherry picked from commit f7fbf480daf8dbb09650a6de4f21c1a487bfdedb)

Change-Id: Ib9b86ade4cb8317509e218aec31f32e5d08f4035

subject: Sync and cap requirements from all projects
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 308, 'name': 'Thierry Carrez', 'email': 'thierry@openstack.org', 'username': 'ttx'}, {'_account_id': 4146, 'name': 'Clark Boylan', 'email': 'cboylan@sapwetik.org', 'username': 'cboylan'}, {'_account_id': 5263, 'name': 'Jeremy Stanley', 'display_name': 'fungi', 'email': 'fungi@yuggoth.org', 'username': 'fungi', 'status': 'missing, presumed fed'}, {'_account_id': 6476, 'name': 'Thomas Goirand', 'email': 'thomas@goirand.fr', 'username': 'thomas-goirand'}]
messages:
[{'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-27 03:35:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Works for me

Build succeeded.

- gate-requirements-install http://logs.openstack.org/63/48563/1/check/gate-requirements-install/21df44e : SUCCESS in 7m 00s
'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2013-09-30 08:57:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2013-10-04 20:37:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Could you explain why you arbitrarily "cap them less than or equal to the latest package versions"? This seem to be to be unreasonable. What if a newer version of a package is out, but is completely backward compatible, then it gets packaged in a distribution? Wouldn't this kind of requirement just fail for no reasons? Many times, there was such a case, where a project just arbitrarily caps to "the latest version", then builds just fail because of that. I would prefer this doesn't become the standard way of doing things in OpenStack.'}, {'account_id': 5263, 'date': '2013-10-05 17:04:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

The goal is to no longer need to worry about whether external changes to dependencies which are not under our control will cause stable branches to suddenly be untestable. There has been very minimal interest from stable support teams in watching the results of periodic bitrot jobs and aggressively addressing related breakage, so quite frequently security patches end up being delayed simply because we can't test/gate them any longer."}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2013-10-06 18:44:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Well, that's the whole point of why I do not want this kind of patch to get in. If it does, then the gate will artificially be blocked with some older version, and never, we will see things evolve and be maintained for newer ones. However, distributions (like for example Debian Sid, as this is the one where I upload things in) do not stay static, and the dependencies that OpenStack relies on really do have to be updated and checked. Locking packages to a specific version is an illusion.

Yes, in the short term, you will reduce the amount of work. Yes, patches will get in more easily, and there will be less breakage. I get that. Though you *do* want to see the breakage happen, simply because they need to be addressed. Yes, it's painful. But we have no choice."}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2013-10-06 18:49:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Besides this, your patch is wrong in some cases. For example, you are doing: eventlet==0.9.17 though some packages need 0.13.0. Another one: boto==2.1.1. Many packages like for example Nova needs boto>=2.4.0 (it's in its requirements). Nova has also kombu>=2.4.8, and you wrote: kombu==1.0.4. At this point, I have stopped. This patch is a mess. Please do not approve it."}, {'account_id': 5263, 'date': '2013-10-06 19:22:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

A couple of notes... First, I'm only doing this for existing *stable* release branches (folsom and grizzly). The corresponding branches of openstack/requirements are currently IN NO WAY accurate for those releases since they were branched from master during the havana development cycle. Second, this is an attempt to normalize a set of requirements against which we test patches for those older supported releases--because we weren't applying any requirements controls during those release cycles there are in fact conflicting requirements between some projects from that timeframe. There is unfortunately some need to adjust requirements of some projects in stable release branches to match. You should be aware that this is happening anyway when integration tests run, since one and only one version of a requirement can be installed at a time, so when projects with conflicting requirements are tested together the versions of requirements are not clearly defined and prone to a somewhat random last-installed version decision.

Keep in mind that this is purely for the sake of defining the versions of dependencies we test older stable branches against. In theory downstream distro package maintainers have already decided what versions of these requirements they are carrying back when that particular OpenStack integrated release occurred. Starting with the havana release, we have more automated mechanisms to enforce requirements consistency and propose updates to projects which fall out of compliance, so one conversation which still needs to happen is whether we apply hard caps on those requirements at havana release time or looser caps with similar requirements synchronization as applied in the master branch going forward. In the meantime, this is purely at attempt to catch the folsom and grizzly releases up to some sort of consistency.

We get to choose... do we want to test old stable releases against every new version of a dependency which comes out, or do we want timely security fixes for stable branches. It's pretty much one or the other."}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2013-10-07 10:11:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

The only reason why stable branches exist in the first place is to avoid duplication of work between distros, by making everyone work on the same branches (rather than private backport branches). They do not exist to spare the distributions of any work. Nobody (i.e. no distro) is apparently interested in maintaining stable/folsom anymore. The only people that need it to work in some capacity is the vulnerability management team, because we promised some support period for security patches and we need to merge them. If we are the only ones to work on it, we pick the rules. It became our branch.

Distributions can't just drop working on a stable branch and then complain that it's not tested against their preferred set of dependencies. Nobody is looking after the periodic jobs failures. The VMT doesn't have too much time to spend on it, so we simplify the problem by freezing the dependency set as much as we can."}, {'account_id': 5263, 'date': '2013-10-08 13:54:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Work In Progress'}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2013-10-09 06:48:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

You wrote: "In theory downstream distro package maintainers have already decided what versions of these requirements they are carrying back when that particular OpenStack integrated release occurred." Well, this works for stable releases of distributions, though for rolling releases (like Gentoo, or with Sid), this isn't the case.

Then you wrote: "We get to choose... do we want to test old stable releases against every new version of a dependency which comes out, or do we want timely security fixes for stable branches. It's pretty much one or the other." Well, when it comes to Debian, I'm interested of having such thing (eg: stable dependency set) for Essex, not for Folsom, and soon, not for Grizzly (when I will overwrite Grizzly with Havana in Sid and Testing), though OpenStack upstream doesn't maintain Essex, and goes to have fixed dependencies for Folsom and Grizzly, which is in my case, and in the case of Ubuntu 12.10 and 13.04, not matching what is happening. Currently, I would like that Grizzly is tested against anything that appears in Debian Sid, because this is the reality I have to address.'}, {'account_id': 5263, 'date': '2013-10-11 02:34:08.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-11 02:39:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

commit_message:
Sync and cap requirements from all projects

* global-requirements.txt: Rebuild the list by installing
run-time and test requirements, including all transitive
dependencies, and cap them less than or equal to the latest package
versions unless they're for libraries we control.

Closes-Bug: 1172418
Change-Id: I615e1350d8a35718f4f7ac677447f7c4e7a78f7a

commit_message:
xenapi: enforce filters after live-migration

Currently and network filters, including security groups, are
lost after a server has been live-migrated.

This partially fixes the issue by ensuring that security groups are
re-applied to the VM once it reached the destination, and been started.

This leaves a small amount of time during the live-migrate where the VM
is not protected. There is a further bug raised to close the rest of
this whole, but this helps keep the VM protected for the majority of the
time.

Fixes bug 1202266

(Cherry picked from commit: 5cced7a6dd32d231c606e25dbf762d199bf9cca7)

Change-Id: Ib2e7162a57474f43a94dbc9b14b902ab63bea5c6

commit_message:
xenapi: apply firewall rules in finish_migrate

When security groups were added, the rules were not re-applied to
servers that have been migrated to a new hypervisor.

This change ensures the firewall rules are applied as part of creating
the new VM in finish_migrate. This code follows a very similar pattern
to the code in spawn, and that is where the cut and paste code comes
from. This code duplication was removed in Havana.

Fixes bug 1073306

Change-Id: I6295a782df328a759e358fb82b76dd3f7bd4b39e

role assignment when the role hadn't been used before would
actually add the role assignment and would not return a

commit_message:
Fix remove role assignment adds role using LDAP assignment

When using the LDAP assignment backend, attempting to remove a
role assignment when the role hadn't been used before would
actually add the role assignment and would not return a
404 Not Found like the SQL backend.

This change makes it so that when attempt to remove a role that
wasn't assigned then 404 Not Found is returned.

Closes-Bug: #1242855
Change-Id: I28ccd26cc4bb1a241d0363d0ab52d2c11410e8b3

Move version code into separate file and set pbr version to 2014.1.0

This structure is used in most of the OpenStack projects.

commit_message:
Adds basic plumbing for RESTful API service using Pecan+WSME

This patch adds some basic plumbing for a Solum RESTful API service
using Pecan+WSME.

addresses blueprint rest-api-base

commit_message:
Add a solum-api command

There are a couple of reviews up for deciding on the REST API
infrastructure.  Regardless which is picked, they will need a solum-api
command that serves up the API.  This commit puts those base pieces in
place.

Part of blueprint rest-api-base

Change-Id: Ie7d22d3ece0e81eca7959ad2d3ba5d756264d797

[{'created': '2013-11-03 23:36:38.000000000', 'message': "Import logging from oslo-incubator

commit_message:
Import logging from oslo-incubator

The oslo-incubator repository of shared OpenStack code includes a
logging lib.  Import it and its depenencies.

For more information about oslo-incubator and using code from there,
see: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Oslo#Incubation

This code was pulled from oslo-incubator at commit
cbfded9c0ddc80cf5422a0d65ffbd8e9a8714d45.

Part of blueprint logging

Change-Id: I2f6a2cf564903d1273105a4acedcc83e89cb207b

Using the mandatory option of WSME on Ports

custom validation code on Ports.

commit_message:
API Ports node_id attribute to be unicode only

To be consistent node_id should not accept integer type.

This patch also improve some docstrings.

Change-Id: Ib003928eaa0981f1a6dc25a2610b04e4cca22ebe
Partial-Bug: #1251549

commit_message:
Use vmdk descriptor to populate image properties

image_upload.sh doesn't use the descriptor properties embedded inside
the vmdk file. This requires the user to manually change the filename of the
vmdk file to add the properties (disk type, storage adapter and network
adapter).
In case of a sparse monolithic sparse or stream-optimized sparse, these
properties are extracted from the descriptor.
The user can still override these values by modifying the filename.

Change-Id: I1734311c66efe60a1a30e3ea63cc2a9da9cdb5b4
Closes-Bug: #1247300

commit_message:
Use the oslo db database connection for Heat

This is the preferred configuration now, and sql_connection is
deprecated.

commit_message:
change assertEquals to assertEqual

According to http://docs.python.org/2/library/unittest.html
assertEquals is a deprecated alias of assertEqual.

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/56652/ updates to a new version of
hacking that enforces H602. Turning that on requires this change to land
first.

Re-do of https://review.openstack.org/#/c/53510 since that is abandoned.

Change-Id: Ie621edc8770e2015df5712f77d4cf9679b02bd0f

commit_message:
Convert to modern form of openstack-common.conf

The new conf style is one module per line. Modules are also sorted
alphabetically. There are no changes in imports, but this makes it
easier to keep imports up to date.

Change-Id: I727abcaead5840032618ea03554879e896efb425

commit_message:
Add context to TaskManager.node object

Task managers contain a short cut to the node(s) they are managing.
We should be using this more throughout the code, but I ran into a
problem trying to call task.node.save() -- the node RPC object
was created without a context.

This patch is a simple hack to work around our @objectify decorator,
by adding the task's context directly to the node RPC object.

Now it is possible to do this:

  with task_manager.acquire(...) as task:
    node = task.node
    # do something with node
    node.save()

Change-Id: Ie340415d5a4bcc44507d36700a234a8c34fd9457

commit_message:
fix help text in "Create An image" window

In the "Create An image" window, there are "minimum disk" and "minimun
memory" text input. But both help text on the two text inputs are using
"the minimum disk size...". Actually for the second one we should say
"the minimum memory size...", and now this patch fix this.

Change-Id: Ife19acba5fafb41d99e9416d2f9e8082b9eaef53

commit_message:
Fix bug with test dublicationd for test run

Before this fix when test run was started and this test run must have
included tests that had been executed earlier with another test run
multiple copies for current test run were created which leads to
messed up ui. To avoid this query for tests from which copies will be
created was extended to provide correct results.

Change-Id: I8b9cca4c57ee973e4f818ecdc6079b24f108f555

commit_message:
Add taskflow (used by cinder + others) to requirements

Taskflow (a stackforge based library) targeted at helping
openstack projects with state management and consistency
is now offically a library and to remove the cinder local
copy we need to add it as a requirement.

Change-Id: Ic112d707b3d914481da41adbb6aa9d8b890742df

commit_message:
Provide a way of determining init system used

dib-init-system script is installed into $PATH. Called
without arguments it will print the name of init system
used to stdout.

Additionally, set DIB_INIT_SYSTEM environment variable to
the init system used.

Tested on ubuntu+upstart, centos+upstart, fedora+systemd,
debian+sysv.

Closes-Bug: #1251610

Change-Id: I29668079091f6060dab66d8259890384d3bbd653

commit_message:
Abstract out DB operations on deploys in db.deploy

The db.deploy module contains the Deployment class with an abstract
methods. Those methods provides high levels operations on the
deployments.

Change-Id: Ibca797832ebbc96247703cdfc8b0958d10a71ddd
Implements: blueprint independent-deploy

commit_message:
Added Deployment model

This patch is the first step of the separation of deployments from
tasks. The Deployment model represents an installation of OpenStack.
This model is related with the Task model through a many-to-one
relation. Now the relattion is optional because Task.deployment_uuid can
be nullable. It will be fixed in next patches.

The db.api was extended by a deployment function. The functions provide
operations to create, get, update and delete deployments.

This patch also adds index for the field uuid of the Task model.

Change-Id: I41bef0ccebdc27cd97b1db663ff3d8a9f0a5509d
Implements: blueprint independent-deploy

commit_message:
Refactor API error handling

Refactor the API error handling to ensure error messages are translated.
Since wsme 0.5b6, the error message doesn't need to be converted to
unicode, wsme handles it for us.

Related bug #1200518

Change-Id: Iec396f045cd3afe817301f0d00917c42c7587b55

This bumps eventlet past what's available in Precise, and thus make Swift uninstallable on a clean install of that OS.

Granted, it may be that Swift is broken right now since it doesn't seem to work with eventlet 0.9.16, but maybe that should be fixed in Swift.

Three options:

1) Bump the requirements past what's available in Precise
2) Work around it in Swift
3) Figure out how to get Precise repos to include 0.9.17"}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2013-11-15 00:20:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Closes-Bug: #1244597

commit_message:
Fix eventlet version in requirements to >=0.9.17

Version 0.9.16 does not account current_size correctly in pools.Pool,
making the unit test test_memcached.py:test_connection_pooling fail.

Change-Id: I7e9ec7324f512b510c76f27aafa9b4132b5a231b
Closes-Bug: #1244597

commit_message:
Drop auth_token configs for api-paste.ini.

We now prefer to use nova.conf to configure keystoneclients
auth_token configs.

Also, Devstack has now been update to allow this:

  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/52258/

Change-Id: I2a4b300af37eddf5010b97ca796f0552941642a8

commit_message:
Import install_venv from oslo

The new version of install_venv_common evaluates requirements.txt
and test-requirements.txt at the same time and we avoid Django 1.6
is installed when evaluating django-nose dependencies.

Change-Id: I2ab7108b3615ac6c0525089b81b80e5c0a4793fc
Closes-Bug: #1250581

commit_message:
Fix import log_handler error with publish_errors set

Sync from Olso.
Commit Id is Ibf28ba17f81b5ddeda653f6a3501ecac18ffcd42

This handler sends all error logs as rpc notifications.
Note: when using publish_errors you also need to set the
notification_driver option too.

Closes-bug: #1240349
Change-Id: Ie66b23af8da2e439e0ac2f5677f6a064e3dd3133

commit_message:
Add support for limiting and sorting stacks

This adds support to the stacks index call for limit, sort_keys,
sort_dir, and marker query parameters, allowing users of the API to
retrieve a subset of stacks.

With this commit, stacks are also sorted by created_at DESC by default.

blueprint pagination

Change-Id: Ib20cfae183475ff42deda82168b8b9c8d043ecd0

Add links section to the stacks index response

Add a `links` section to the stacks index response that will contain
pagination links for the collection - this commit includes adding a
`next` link to the section.

commit_message:
Fix some direct imports from sqlalchemy

Directly import sqlalchemy might result in some inconsistent
behaviors. It would bypass the db_backend configuration.

Change-Id: Ic07c5d9f4898add6629a296ee1dff22be0e75262

commit_message:
Use openstack git repos when possible

We now prefer git.openstack.org to github.com. Use
openstack git repo URIs in source-repository-*
files of projects we host.

Change-Id: I81c393461efee80f9aa8f540369fdfe32f0d159b

commit_message:
Allow use of oslo.messaging-1.3.0a1

Mainly needed for the Nova port since we think we've fixed some issues
affecting cells.

Full list since 1.2.0a11:

 7914181 Properly handle transport URL config on the client
 9853fc6 Updated from global requirements
 2ec1fb7 Properly handle transport:///vhost URL
 c59e04f Replace assertEquals with assertEqual
 1dc1709 Updated from global requirements
 3a2a4d9 Make rpc_backend default to 'rabbit'
 b2cef24 Updated from global requirements
 5af4478 Add third element to RPC versions for backports
 5f76009 Apply six for metaclass
 91f74d8 Fix rpc client docs
 f0ad97b Updated from global requirements
 a1b57a5 Remove cruft from setup.cfg
 2aa1dc6 Updated from global requirements
 86f2e74 Fixes a typo in the address string syntax
 b6d8087 Implement the server side of ZmqDriver
 a2d1131 Add zmq-receiver
 5d3fc9c Implement the client side of ZmqDriver
 ff3a415 Import zmq driver code with minimal modifications

Change-Id: I5646f586b3b16b173b13b3ad1a5d355ef6033cb3

commit_message:
Required fields on nodes

Make the 'chassis_id' and 'driver' fields mandatory when creating or
updating a node, also validate those fields to see if the information
inputed is correct (if the chassis exists and the driver is supported).

This patch also fixes the return code of the _convert_chassis_uuid_to_id()
method, just like in ports.py the conversion method should return 400
(Bad Request) instead of 404 (Not Found).

Change-Id: Idde5e51669ec29382ed36e6e9658ef01aff2434f

commit_message:
Cherry-picks from release-0.3

* Stripping error messages in services list
* Fixed issue when '# is required' with 1 instance
* Fix importing ordereddict for python2.7 (ubuntu).
* Fix drop-down lists in IE9.
* Fix name for clusterIp property
* Resolved issue with checkbox layouts
* Fix not working widgetMedia in boolean fields.
* No need to restart Web-server now to see changes in dynamic UI.

Change-Id: I42785d21d61faae1c8adbc3a9b0d7afe84a1d2a4

There are two types of attached disks, VMDK (see _attach_volume_vmdk) or iSCSI (see _attach_volume_iscsi).

I agree for VMDK disks, we should not detroy the VMDK file.
But for iSCSI volumes attached as RDM disk, an RDM vmdk file was created to attached to the VM, the file contains only iSCSI volume information that describes the mapping to the LUN on the ESXi host. See create_virtual_disk_spec and attach_disk_to_vm. revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-18 14:49:33.000000000', 'message': 'VMware: Detach volume should not delete vmdk

During volume detach a delete_virtual_disk_spec is used to remove
the device from the running instance. This spec also "destroy" the
underlying vmdk file, this is not right, we should not delete vmdk
file when detach it from a VM instance.

The fix was remove the fileOperation field of the device config
so that the vmdk file will not be destroyed. Also I changed the
function name from delete_virtual_disk_spec to remove_virtual_disk_spec
which is more accurate.

Change-Id: Ibd218d6a8cfeede4f5ca74f28bc0c3d0c185bb14
Closes-Bug: #1241350

commit_message:
VMware: Detach volume should not delete vmdk

During volume detach a delete_virtual_disk_spec is used to remove
the device from the running instance. This spec also "destroy" the
underlying vmdk file, this is not right, we should not delete vmdk
file when detach it from a VM instance.

The fix was remove the fileOperation field when detach vmdk volume
so as to make sure the volume will not be destroyed; but for iscsi
we still need to destroy the volume.

Also I changed the function name from delete_virtual_disk_spec to
detach_virtual_disk_spec which is more accurate.

Change-Id: Ibd218d6a8cfeede4f5ca74f28bc0c3d0c185bb14
Closes-Bug: #1241350

commit_message:
Nova-all: Replace basestring by six for python3 compatability

The builtin basestring abstract type was removed in python3,
use str instead, we need to using six.string_types to replace
the basestring for py3 compatibility.

Partial Implements bp: basestring-py3-compatible

Change-Id: I17e87e49e7ebf3cc9c391e9beace8c45d2d2b689

I'm okay with raising the exception at the sqlalchemy level.  Though, in the future, if we end up with another layer in parallel with sqlalchemy (objects or direct DB queries or whatever), the check would have to be repeated there.  So moving the check up to the API level at that point would save duplicated code.

But, that's a future problem not a current problem, and this is a very small simple patch that does one useful thing and does it well, so I'm +1 on the current patch.  We can easily move the validation later if we actually need to."}, {'account_id': 5292, 'date': '2013-11-13 01:16:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 16: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Here's my 2c re: testing in the REST API layer or not. We actually have several layers of abstract here, the REST API, the network API and then the db api. In a way the current REST API for floating ips is broken because the format of floating ip ids used depend on the network backend. This difference should not be visible to the REST API user.

However, we can't really change that now and the V2 API is going away eventually anyway. However, we already have a network api abstraction level that removes the need for the REST API to know about whether it needs to do neutron specific calls or nova network specific calls. We just call network_api.get_floating_ip and we get the nova network or neutron version depending on what is currently in use and thats where I believe the validation correctly belongs.

Francisco - this is where I apologise to you for recommending that you put it in the db layer. Although that is ok, as David mentions it potentially has duplication issues if we end up with something run in parallel with sqlalchemy. If we instead put it in just above - in nova/network/api.py in get_floating_ip (this is the nova-network version of the network api) then we'll get the same behaviour and not need to worry about future underlying db implementation issues. The test would then go in nova/tests/network/test_api.py.

I think this is a straightforward change to the patch, feel free to ping me if you want a hand."}, {'account_id': 8810, 'date': '2013-11-14 13:30:08.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 17.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-14 14:04:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 17: Works for me

commit_message:
Raising exception for invalid floating_ip's ID

The proposal is to validate the ID from the request to check
whether it is is valid for nova-network driver.
If the network driver is nova-network, the ID should be numeric.

Change-Id: I10df4f9ba2f5cfec7a6d2112cf5905944a9b5419
Closes-bug: #1078055

commit_message:
Avoid unnecessary admin auth with Neutron to get network info

Currently _build_nw_info_model always authenticated with Neutron
using the configured Neutron admin credentials, but often it is
called in the context of the user that owns the Instance (for
example at the end of allocate_for_instance()) and so this
additional authentication is unnecessary.

Change-Id: I5414dadb8358104723fe62734a4471bec87006c1
Closes-Bug: 1250848

messages:

Build succeeded.

- gate-tripleo-incubator-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/10/56010/2/check/gate-tripleo-incubator-docs/76e76fd/doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 27s

(2 inline comments)

"}, {'account_id': 1926, 'date': '2013-11-12 15:14:30.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-12 15:15:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Works for me

Build succeeded.

- gate-tripleo-incubator-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/10/56010/3/check/gate-tripleo-incubator-docs/72ffefd/doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 26s
'}, {'account_id': 8041, 'date': '2013-11-12 15:25:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-11-13 01:45:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I think this should be passed in via Heat instead. That avoids all the guff with sshing to hosts that might be offline at the time or whatever."}, {'account_id': 1926, 'date': '2013-11-13 10:12:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Ok, I can look into adding this via Heat but my first reaction would be that this should be driven from outside of the hosts as operators would require a lot of flexibility to build their ringfile.

so just to clarify

this would mean that each swift node will need to be passed in the IP of all other heat nodes and the list of storage devices used on each heat node. Also in future the size of each storage devices would need to be passed in via heat so an appropriate weighting can be applied to each device.

In fact now that I think about it, this may not work at all for multiple hosts, I'm thinking maybe the same ring file needs to be used on each swift node (to insure the same mappings are used), if this is the case I will need to create the ringfile once and distribute the same file to all hosts (which means fixing this script)"}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-11-13 10:16:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

So, we may need to iterate yes. I wasn't proposing a distributed regeneration, rather than we create the ring once and inject it to all nodes via heat. Thats your last paragraph, I believe."}, {'account_id': 1926, 'date': '2013-11-13 10:21:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Ok, makes sense, will investigate.'}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2013-11-13 23:26:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

pert power of 18 is probably way too high. see http://rackerlabs.github.io/swift-ppc/

Also, a replica count of 1 is probably not a good idea.

Also, swift-ring-builder rebalance can take a seed so that all machines can generate the same ring file. See the usage string for details. If this is used or not, it still needs to be the same ring on all machines.'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-11-13 23:42:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

On IRC John said that we can inject the file, or inject the parameters including seed - it's up to us.

I'd be happy with each swift node calculating the same ring based on heat parameters (and o-r-c orchestrating that). I suspect installing swift in the devtest environment every time is undesirable, so lets go the distributed route."}, {'account_id': 1926, 'date': '2013-11-14 01:15:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Thanks For chiming in John

The part power of 18 is only the default in this script, when using the script in devtest I'm setting "--part-power 10", https://review.openstack.org/#/c/56011/3/scripts/devtest_overcloud.sh

I'm also only setting the replica level to 1 because this is an all in one install but agreed the default level for this script should be higher, 3?

So if I generate the ringfile on multiple machines with the same seed this would be equivalent to generating the file once and distributing the file?

Distrubute route to generate the file sounds good to me, I had just finished a version of this that generates the ringfiles on the first host and then scp's it to other file,  still avoiding installing swift on the devtest host, I'll scrap that idea now.'}, {'account_id': 1926, 'date': '2013-11-15 09:59:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Abandoned

This is now part of the swift element in t-i-e'}]

commit_message:
Add script to configure swift ring files

Adding a script "scripts/swift-init-ring" can be used to create a
ring file on multiple hosts. This script is not ideal as it creates
the ring file on each host. We can't create it on the host running
the script as we don't have access to swift-ring-builder, alternatively
I could install swift on this host but this didn't seem like a nice
alternative.

Change-Id: I21f77124b4edb34849e9b75ddea343c222709fa4

tenant_network_types option of ML2 neutron core plugin
defaults to 'local' (i.e. no communications beyond one
physical machine). We must use 'gre' tenant networks
instead, just like we did for OVS neutron plugin.

Closes-Bug: #1251166

Change-Id: I3779412ac6ee2d7291a8a4dc52c7e1fea79a54b7
"}]
commit_message:
Fix config of ML2 plugin in neutron element

tenant_network_types option of ML2 neutron core plugin
defaults to 'local' (i.e. no communications beyond one
physical machine). We must use 'gre' tenant networks
instead, just like we did for OVS neutron plugin.

Closes-Bug: #1251166

Change-Id: I3779412ac6ee2d7291a8a4dc52c7e1fea79a54b7

[{'created': '2013-11-10 22:45:07.000000000', 'message': "UserAuthInfo use dependency injection

UserAuthInfo didn't use dependency injection so the managers were
created multiple times.

The dependency injection doesn't happen until after __init__(),
so users can't call methods using the dependencies in __init__().

Change-Id: I3d649ec45d5d7ade740277334c32d9f76140fb34
"}]
commit_message:
UserAuthInfo use dependency injection

UserAuthInfo didn't use dependency injection so the managers were
created multiple times.

The dependency injection doesn't happen until after __init__(),
so users can't call methods using the dependencies in __init__().

Change-Id: I3d649ec45d5d7ade740277334c32d9f76140fb34

commit_message:
Rework TableField to enable actions inside modal form.

They are implemented inside `clean` method of a TableField. This
commit just provides a basis for actual actions implementation: they
should be called inside `clean` method - either via DataTable
instance, or with direct calls to metadataclient.

Also, should fix datagrid in MS SQL Cluster (it is broken by this
commit) and fix styles for messages about actions (right now they look
like validation errors, which is not true).

Change-Id: Iae638f36cb3d43d18b763412779ddf09ccc58e7f

commit_message:
Use get_secgroup_uuids in Instance

Instance._get_security_groups_id serves the same
purpose as neutron.get_secgroup_uuids. This change switches
Instance to using get_secgroup_uuids instead.

Updating the test has the side-effect on getting full test
coverage on get_secgroup_uuids, albeit indirectly.

Change-Id: I8cdc51692fd8d96e68c6c947891c9708f77d54c3
Related-Bug: #1250286

[{'account_id': 7193, 'date': '2013-11-14 09:58:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I had a quick look at the proposed changes and have a general question (maybe due to lack of knowledge how exactly globalization in python and openstack works):

What is the general strategy for translation? Translate each and every string, or just translate some (e.g. exceptions and other stuff that an end user would see)? For example, does it make sense to translate log debug messages, or wouldn't it be better to keep them english only, since developers have to be able to read them?

In an internal product development project, we have the rule that everything up to a certain log level is kept en_US only to make it readable by technical folks, and translate all exceptions, HTTP error message or high log levels which a user could see.

... what I'm trying to say: some stuff must be English, so a developer can read it when a customer sends log files for problem analysis. But again, maybe openstack always keeps English log files and I just lack the knowledge how it works ;-)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-14 10:17:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Works for me

commit_message:
Add _() to fix i18N compliance (part 1)

In heat, almost 200 log message and at least 30 exception
message are not processed by _(), and will not been translated.
We should use '_("STRING ...")' to enable i18n support.

I will split to two parts for review easier because the files
lost of _() are too much.

Closes-Bug: #1249217

Change-Id: I2c86dc7770a7f6f107ba16711b9cba363ef9b906

commit_message:
Ensure swift-container-sync service is enabled

* The ubuntu cloud packages are missing an upstart config
and /etc/init.d wrapper for the swift-container-sync service.
This adds them if missing on the ubuntu platform so that we can
start this service successfully.
* Ensure the swift-container-sync is enabled and running
when allowed_sync_hosts is defined
* Swauth requires its own separate declaration of
allowed_sync_hosts in the proxy configuration as well

Change-Id: I638d43445edfd1f9519911212942ac8d69d4fff2

change assertEquals to assertEqual

According to http://docs.python.org/2/library/unittest.html
assertEquals is a deprecated alias of assertEqual.

commit_message:
AuthInfo use dependency injection

AuthInfo didn't use dependency injection so the managers were
created multiple times.

The dependency injection doesn't happen until after __init__(),
so users can't call methods using the dependencies in __init__().

Change-Id: I4532a2219385f2e303eb6f9a7bd7edb76046e331

The whole structure of how this is refactored needs a re-think. Core issues:

- The current design stemmed from the CS team needing to override Swift behavior. Instead, think of how a Swift core team member would approach this...and refactor in the cleanest way.

- You need to move Keystone stuff into python-keystoneclient. You cannot import keystoneclient into Swift. The Swift team are removing python-swiftclient from swift repo.'}, {'account_id': 1916, 'date': '2013-11-15 06:28:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (4 inline comments)

Swift have no dependency on python-keystoneclient today? I thought it is using the auth_token middleware

I'm still confused as to why this strong coupling with the taskflow data model needs to happen? It seems this is just attaching an arbitrary set of object state to a flow, and then on flow state transitions it is saving that information on what object may have been changed directly in the flow.

The part that I'm unsure about is why the notification system can't do this same thing. Listen for flow state changes, and then maintain this object change information in that mechanism instead, and u can persist it in the flow or outside of the flow (in another table). At that point its really not taskflows concern about what object transitions occurred or there correspondence to the flow state transitions.

Lets maybe discuss more on IRC?"}, {'account_id': 2401, 'date': '2013-11-01 23:43:13.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-01 23:44:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: Doesn't seem to work

Thanks for starting this. I'm still unsure if we have to go that way. Some of my concerns are:

- using flow metadata to simulate many-to-many relationship between flows and resources does not look right;
- as far as I can see, object transitions are not persistent, so if flow is later loaded to different engine (e.g. after service restart), object will stuck in old status;
- is 1:1 mapping for flow states -> object status correct model? status may depend on which tasks are running or already finished; if that is not the case, two statuses look enough: describing what flow does to that resource, and maybe what resource status will be when flow finishes successfully."}, {'account_id': 7349, 'date': '2013-11-07 11:35:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

If some information about objects is required outside of the flow, then tasks and flow notifications can be used to watch on flow execution. It is better to implement some external tables of properties and save some data about objects being operates by flows. Because, when we have a job board with a lot of flows posted on it and some of these flows are run by some executors, you'll have to iterate through the whole job board looking on flow statuses and gathering information about your objects."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-11-15 06:03:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

commit_message:
Statuses for objects performed by flow

This patch provide functionality for storing statuses of objects on
which flow is performed. This can be usefull if flow should not change
status of objects, but information about this should be stored.

Change-Id: Ic7b0c6b727a11710dea907e6cb5b95fd6a8e6023

commit_message:
Update help msgs to reflect usage of NOVA_XXX vars

nova-client will take in account NOVA_USERNAME, NOVA_PASSWORD and
NOVA_PROJECT_ID if OS_XXX counterpart are missing.
Let the user know that this is an expected behaviour to avoid
confusion when silently accepting those values.

Change-Id: I5f4eb8958b95aa907e6217874eb17283706e7a32
Closes-Bug: #1061491

commit_message:
More instance_type -> flavor renames in db.api

Renames the instance_type methods in db.api to flavor and converts the
tests to match. Updates doc strings where needed.

Note that this patch doesn't rename anything touching the db models for
instance types, that will be handled in a later patch for the blueprint.

Part of bp flavor-instance-type-dedup

Change-Id: I397421c9b34d295368999c5d085345409945151a

commit_message:
Wire up support for DEVSTACK_GATE_SMOKE_SERIAL

We want to default to running smoke tests in parallel, but that won't
work in neutron so add a serial mode that can be explicitly set.

Change-Id: Ia659fd7016458f6ba4d4d43ec5811cd830ddd22d

commit_message:
Managed Cloud compatibility for Cloud Servers

Make the Cloud Servers resource aware of the Managed Cloud automation.
The Cloud Servers resource should wait for the Managed Cloud automation
to complete before proceeding with the server configuration.

Blueprint managed-cloud

commit_message:
Convert to a more modern form of openstack-common.conf

One module per line is the new hotness. I've also sorted the
modules alphabetically. There are no changes to your imports, but
this makes it easier for oslo maintainers to keep your imports up
to date.

Change-Id: I7581f4ad2ed853742a98aa6d6d4e9e0aeebce8fa

commit_message:
Work around new hacking check import problem

The new hacking 0.8 tries to import modules to ensure that they're
modules. This would fail on the keystoneclient.tests.client_fixtures
module because it tried to open files that didn't exist.

This workaround just ignores the failure of trying to open files
during import.

Change-Id: Ica243401fb7e111379aa0bf229705d4a4e8c9b6e

commit_message:
Apply six for metaclass

The way to using metaclass has changed in Python3.

Python 2.7 way:

class Foo(object):
  __metaclass__ = FooMeta

Python 3 way:

class Foo(object, metaclass=FooMeta):
  ...

The six.add_metaclass() decorator allows us to use one syntax that
works for both Python 2.7 and Python 3.

Change-Id: I08703a8b2927f45f4705fe085368d1ebd78b02fa
Closes-Bug: #1236648

commit_message:
Do not name variables as builtins

According to HACKING.rst [1] we should not name anything as a builtin.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/keystone/blob/master/HACKING.rst#general

Change-Id: I0f34b252ea395b6c87e6738f334fbae9e194134b

commit_message:
Add flavor-manage to core for V3 API

Adds the flavor-manage plugin to the core list for the V3 API.
This is part of the process of adding all of the flavor related
extensions to core, with the exception of rxtx, as per the discussion
here: https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/NovaV3APICore

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api

DocImpact

Change-Id: Idbedce5cc5936abc52235cd40573c8fe841f24fe

commit_message:
Fix DB integrity issues when using postgres

The IntegrityError faced on network deletion that
spooks Tempest tests is most likely caused by the
fact that the ml2 plugin does a dirty read. By
adding a 'select for update' we should be able to
address the issue once and for all.

Also, there's a chance that the dhcp port gets
reallocated while we are deleting the network. To
this aim, catch the integrity error and attempt
to recover from it.

This patch also removes the handling of errors
on concurrent reads that can no longer occur when
deleting the network.

(Hopefully) Closes-bug: #1239637

PS: This fix may be relevant for bugs #1243726 and #1246737

Change-Id: Iefae7fc8a903cc35d8bf80fc4cee533b7f64032c

commit_message:
Rewrite get_secgroup_uuids to avoid resource_by_refid

get_secgroup_uuids has changed in the following ways:
* No longer attempts to find a security group name via
  a resource_by_refid lookup. resource_by_refid only exists
  as a workaround for AWS compatibility resource which are
  not backed by an API. Usage of resource_by_refid should be
  avoided in native resources if at all possible.
* If the security group looks like a UUID, assume it is
  a UUID for a security group that exists
* Call client.list_security_groups only once, and only if
  there is a non-uuid security group specified
* Do not attempt to reduce duplicate security groups to a unique
  list. If that is important for resources it can be done in
  validation.
* Raise PhysicalResourceNotFound if name maps to no group
* Raise PhysicalResourceNameAmbiguity if name maps to more than one
  group

Change-Id: I106adc15a7882192884d37c0806947470d139434
Closes-Bug: #1250286

[{'created': '2013-10-26 06:38:58.000000000', 'message': "Remove deprecated fields in keystone auth middleware

This commit makes the following changes:

Use X_PROJECT_ID instead of X_TENANT_ID:
  In the latest keystone auth_token middleware it is recommended to
  use X_PROJECT_ID instead of X_TENANT_ID. X_PROJECT_ID is supported
  in auth_token middleware for both keystone v2 and v3 API.
  The corresponding change was done in keystoneclient before Grizzly
  release, so we don't need to take care of X_TENANT_ID now.

USE X_ROLES instead of X_ROLE:
  X_ROLES is now recommended.
  X_ROLE exists just for diablo backward compatibility.

Remove X_TENANT and X_USER:
  X_TENANT and X_USER are for diablo backward compatibility.
  We no longer need take care of them in Icehouse Neutron.

Change-Id: Ie714b1323ff8c44dbee66b54e683226cf675b104
Closes-Bug: #1242447
"}]
commit_message:
Remove deprecated fields in keystone auth middleware

This commit makes the following changes:

Use X_PROJECT_ID instead of X_TENANT_ID:
  In the latest keystone auth_token middleware it is recommended to
  use X_PROJECT_ID instead of X_TENANT_ID. X_PROJECT_ID is supported
  in auth_token middleware for both keystone v2 and v3 API.
  The corresponding change was done in keystoneclient before Grizzly
  release, so we don't need to take care of X_TENANT_ID now.

USE X_ROLES instead of X_ROLE:
  X_ROLES is now recommended.
  X_ROLE exists just for diablo backward compatibility.

Remove X_TENANT and X_USER:
  X_TENANT and X_USER are for diablo backward compatibility.
  We no longer need take care of them in Icehouse Neutron.

Change-Id: Ie714b1323ff8c44dbee66b54e683226cf675b104
Closes-Bug: #1242447

Adding basic v2 glance image sharing tests
 * accepting image
 * rejecting image
 * owner cannot change membership status [negative]
 * trying to set invalid status [negative]

Fixing bug #1201136

Change-Id: Ic2f7102b64fc9dc1954b1e569d261baaaac9a184

commit_message:
Add special serial smoke option

We want smoketests to be parallel by default (for grenade etc), but that won't work
for neutron, so add a special case. Since we don't want to break
anything making this switch, it has to be done in 3 steps:

1) this patch
2) make neutron use smoke-serial
3) change smoke to be parallel

Change-Id: I03ded120c0b496026e39f14f6715624a91ac7558

commit_message:
Fixes wrong Qpid protocol configuration

notify_qpid.py is suffering from the same issue as described in
launchpad bug https://bugs.launchpad.net/oslo/+bug/1158807.
Instead of setting connection.transport, it is attempting to
set connection.protocol.

Fixes bug 1243821

Change-Id: Ice3e7ad917c158a5953475809f3f46f48fd6054d
(cherry picked from commit c04ebd1a77d5dcf226812fadab08257207641220)

commit_message:
Arista ML2 mech driver cleanup and integration with portbindings

fixes bug: 1215097

This patch addresses minor cleanups which are the diff between the
original version of the patch which was merged into havana master
branch and the patch that is submitted for merge into stable/havana.

The original patch that was merged into havana master branch is at:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/49086/
The new patch which has been submitted as havana-backport-potential is:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/54447/

This whole excercise came into play because the original patch was not
picked up in havana-rc2 because of missing tag in the bug. Therefore, the
need to submit new patch against stable/havana.

When the new patch was submitted for havana-backport-potential, few very
minor previously commented cleanups were incorporated as well. This
patch brings these minor cleanups into master branch as well. Therefore,
merge of these two patches will bring both master branch and
stable/havana at parity.

Change-Id: I4ec5273c26a27ca52b430a6c7485a44e880a1787

commit_message:
Add shelve/unshelve test of nova APIs

The shelve feature powers off and gets a vm snapshot. Also the unshelve
feature restarts a vm instance from the snapshot.
This patch adds an API test for shelve/unshelve features.

Change-Id: Ica8e8c864371c0e2018b2c7df9c6ecbbeddaf5df
Closes-Bug: 1235695

Fixes bug 1251007

Previously if the AdjustmentType was set to PercentChangeInCapacity,
then depending on the choice of the instance group MinSize and the

commit_message:
Ensure autoscaling actions occur for percentage adjustment

Fixes bug 1251007

Previously if the AdjustmentType was set to PercentChangeInCapacity,
then depending on the choice of the instance group MinSize and the
scale-up policy ScalingAdjustment, no autoscaling actions may occur
even when the under-scaled alarm fires.

This situation occurred if:

   (MinSize * ScalingAdjustment / 100.0) < 1.0

in which case the group never get gets scaled up even if the under-
scaled alarm stays in the alarm state forever.

Now we follow the rounding rules used by AWS Autoscaling:

  http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AutoScaling/latest/DeveloperGuide/as-scale-based-on-demand.html

Change-Id: I79e5e743de1944ace5ef2c4dbcb76c9cab7262bb
(cherry picked from commit 5720e6d647ce3a273d638fd7dacc9c2d6eb2bc22)

assertNotEquals will be deprecated in Python 3.

commit_message:
Replace __metaclass__

The __metaclass__ syntax is not compatible with Python 3, this patch will
replace it with the add_metaclass decorator provided by the six library
which make it easier to add metaclasses that works on both Python 2 and 3.

The patch also grouped some imports as per PEP8.

Change-Id: If4fcee8ec4bb5e7d6971ea5a4143fba6500a09e9
Partial-Bug: #1249886

commit_message:
update Images v2 API to include info about property protections

Updated image-update, image-list, and image-show calls to include
information about the possibility that the cloud provider may have
configured 'property protections', thereby affecting the user's
ability to create/read/update/delete properties.

Revised language in a non-redundant way to reflect the correct
audience for this document.

Change-Id: Ia1b9e2092e105e64199ce2f5d2a32ff7b2675d66
Closes-bug: #1236972

commit_message:
Add project-specific exception to allowed list

The allowed_rpc_exception_modules config option determines what
exceptions are allowed to pass through RPC. The current defaults
do not include project-specific exceptions, usually located at
$project.common.exception. This patch adds that.

Change-Id: Ieb81928465fa73b99a6a14e72bfcabc4d3bbc2f9
Partial-fix: 1250575

commit_message:
Use the cinder upstream api-paste.ini config.

Since we now use the cinder.conf file for keystone
configuration we no longer need to carry this file
in the tripleO element. We can just use the upstream
version.

Change-Id: If8073a0c771c448a3e6450bcbe4cdfcdf2ba58a5

commit_message:
Rename virtapi.instance_type_get to flavor_get

Renames the virtapi.instance_type_get method to flavor_get. Updates the
directly related tests and subclass implementations of VirtAPI.

This patch does not propagate to all related code like conductor API,
that will be handled in a later patch for the blueprint.

Part of bp flavor-instance-type-dedup

Change-Id: Ic47da9aa578d449a4ce542d2d017840f1a8132a7

commit_message:
Add index.rst section for patches merged to master

Add new section called "MASTER" to the release notes, where all patches
that implement blueprints or fix bugs should update the list. This list
will be used for the release notes when a new version is released.

Change-Id: If842bfbb85851fb7a9e22259423da204f4c308f4

Fixes bug 1241467

Narrow-casting statistical aggregates to int before inserting
into the resource usage line charts had the effect of unnaturally
smoothening the trend. This was especially apparent for meters
defined over a narrow range (such as cpu_util ranging from 0.0%
to 100.0%).

commit_message:
Avoid discarding precision of metering data

Fixes bug 1241467

Narrow-casting statistical aggregates to int before inserting
into the resource usage line charts had the effect of unnaturally
smoothening the trend. This was especially apparent for meters
defined over a narrow range (such as cpu_util ranging from 0.0%
to 100.0%).

We now maintain floating point precision for these data.

Change-Id: If6141a4f66aa0078d38aa9f53d913aca5684ad94
(cherry picked from commit 4b973c2fb49b3a1a0d38c3788f45b3af076625d0)

As of Havana the whole api-paste.ini section is incorrect.

api-paste.ini is now considered a distributed source file, and not a configuration file, so it shouldn't be modified by the installer.

Instead, these values in section [keystone_authtoken] of heat.conf should be set:
* auth_host
* auth_port
* auth_protocol
* auth_uri
* admin_tenant_name
* admin_user
* admin_password

And also in section [ec2authtoken]
* auth_uri
* keystone_ec2_uri"}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2013-11-11 07:48:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: No score

Hi Zane,

Thanks for bringing this up.  I don't think a context manager will be useful in this case, since the lock is acquired in the main thread and then passed to the sub-thread.  Doing it this way saves the work of parsing the stack if the lock could not be acquired.  It also allows the user to see the exception, since it's being raised in the main thread."}, {'account_id': 7253, 'date': '2013-10-16 20:18:29.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 7253, 'date': '2013-10-16 20:20:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Zookeeper is a hassle to support in deployments, is not widely packaged, is not implemented in a proper language, and is yet another component in our server dependencies (the others being db, messaging) that would have to be made highly available, scalable, and documented for deployment.  The OpenStack community (and its downstreams) have enough on their plate dealing with the various databases and messaging systems we support that adding a new "server" to the mix that is not grown organically within OpenStack doesn't make alot of sense.

Even "optional" is not suitable to me.  If it were optional, some user will turn it on, and expect the heat developers to support their zookeeper deployment.  We do not want to get into the business of debugging third party software components - we do that already enough with our various db/AMQP implementations.

Please break this change into two patches - one which is base database lock, and one which adds zookeeper functionality.

What is the advantage of using zookeeper over a database lock as specified in your commit log?  From looking at the change set, the database lock doesn't look global, but per stack.  What are the concerns with a db-based lock?'}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-10-26 19:22:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Let me respond first by saying I support the idea of splitting this into 2 patches; 1 with the DB driver, and the 2nd with the ZK driver. I'd actually like even further separation, where the db driver lands first, and then calling code for it lands after, but I'll accept "db driver + calling code" followed by "zk lock driver".

That said, I think you are a bit off base in suggesting that we would somehow be unable to support the code as it is written. We have unit tests, and if somebody adds suppot for it, we can put integration tests with ZK in the gate. Just like nova accepts hyperv (not exactly "in the right language. ;)) so can we accept Zookeeper. Jason has contributed a lot of code and will continue to support this code. It seems to me that he would not have written it without having a use case for it.

Zookeeper locks are far more responsive to failure than the database version.

With the database version each new engine that tries to lock the stack will have to wait 1 hour for the lock to timeout (or more likely, some kind of failover script will manually have to release them). This could only be dropped by making the engine continuously pound the server with updates to refresh the lock.

Zookeeper keeps track of session presence, and thus as soon as the failed engine disconnects and stays disconnected from Zookeeper for the lock timeout period, its locks will be released.

If we can't come to agreement on this, we can always put this driver in contrib, but we'd need to make it loadable as a plugin in a similar fashion as the resource plugins are loadble.

I'd like to hear about a plan for getting multi-engine integration tests into the gate btw. It seems like something that needs some coverage in tempest.'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2013-10-26 21:19:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

I'd also like to come in as an unbiased party and just point out that nova already supports zookeeper via a servicegroup driver. Even if java isn't as nice as python (or maybe jython is, or maybe scala is better, idk) its not something that the openstack community should reject due to it not being home-grown (we must not get become affected by the "not invented here syndrome", especially when it provides useful benefits to provide it).

http://docs.openstack.org/trunk/config-reference/content/zookeeper-servicegroup-driver.html'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-10-28 14:09:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

I think we can all agree that this patch implements two complete features (DB locks and Zookepper locks), and therefore should be split into at least two separate patches.

At this point I would personally lean toward only one of those features being merged.

I am also not a fan of Zookeeper as a dependency. It's not about NIH or squabbling over whether Java is a 'proper' language. It's about whether we as a development team have the capacity to maintain another huge external dependency that we have no control over - particularly one that drags in a whole ecosystem with it, even to the point of competing runtimes &c. I submit that we do not.

I don't believe that making Zookeeper optional solves this problem, because users will still expect us to support it. Therefore our maintenance burden is decreased not at all by having a second implementation. In fact, the only thing that sounds more unpalatable to me than supporting Zookeeper is supporting Zookeeper *and* something else.

IMO we need to decide (maybe at Summit?) whether Zookeeper is something we can afford to depend on or not. Splitting the difference only seems to make things worse."}, {'account_id': 7395, 'date': '2013-10-28 15:23:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

IMO the zookeeper implementation should be put into contrib, and the db lock implementation should be the default. As I understand it Jason originally split his code this way, but was asked to change it by a reviewer. This provides the benefit of keeping non-python and non-community grown code out of our tree (taking away the maintenance pressure) while allowing anyone using heat access to a more production ready locking solution than the db locking. I support the idea of splitting up the patch also.'}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2013-10-28 15:29:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

The arguments for splitting this patch are compelling, so I'll throw my hat in for doing that, however, resistance to pulling in drivers for pluggable features seems counter to other discussions around third party resources and the entire point of having a plug-in system or configurable features.

Our support burden will continue to grow as Heat becomes more popular and real world workloads and use cases start cropping up. IMO we should certainly support the drivers for technologies we don't personally care for.

In this particular case, I'm not married to ZK either, but it certainly should be a choice for this sort of functionality. That being said, its a discussion for the follow-on patch."}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-10-28 17:56:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Andrew, your non-python argument is problematic. If we kicked every non-python dependency out of OpenStack we'd have to write a database server, and queueing engine in python. Zookeeper has a well defined native interface just like RabbitMQ, qpid, PostgreSQL and MySQL.

Optional dependencies increase maintenance burden, yes. IMO this is worth it. The db locking has an issue, and that is poor automatic failure detection. However, it has a benefit, which is a smaller scope. You can see where users with a desire to have a smaller scope will accept the trade-off that the operations will be less automatic. At a small scale this cost is small enough that it can be absorbed.

But users who have any kind of scale will curse our names if we do not provide them a usable option. Zookeeper counts as that usable option. And we shouldn't shy away from supporting the driver unless we have a _better_ option. "Perfect is the enemy of good."'}, {'account_id': 7395, 'date': '2013-10-28 19:03:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Clint while I see your point (and agree that zookeeper is the better locking option), I was providing an alternative for those who do not want this in tree, that still makes the code accessible to anyone who uses heat. This type of compromise helps us get work done without endless back and forth discussion. Also, sqlalchemy abstracts out our mysql/postgress into a dependency on a database, while rabbitmq/qpid are supported by openstack common code which give heat a dependency on the amqp protocol. Both of these cases are slightly different than placing a hard dependency on zookeeper. I like the idea of having a default implementation that anyone can use for development, that is pluggable, and comes with a production ready alternative, outside of the heat main tree.'}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-10-28 21:46:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Thanks Andrew, I understand what you meant better now.

However, if ZK is the only thing that allows real scalability, then it should be in tree and available on the same level.

Perhaps we should take a step back from the whole-stack-lock approach and look at a distributed work-flow approach which would allow spreading the load out on multiple engines without need for a 1:1 stack:engine model.'}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2013-10-28 23:16:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Clint,

I was thinking along same lines as plugin modules plus zookeeper plugin in contrib.  I would +2 that sort of change.'}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2013-10-28 23:23:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

Andrew,

In the case of amqp or SQL implementations, every OpenStack (or nearly?) has a hard dependency on these server technologies.  Hence, every project shares in the burden of documenting, maintaining, scaling, and providing HA for said server.  If all of OpenStack adopted zookeeper for various distributed features, then I'd be on board, but I don't feel it is in our best interest to trailblaze the introduction of such a huge dependency.  We are not talking about a library, but a separate server process with an entirely different development model then OpenStack for only one project (heat), which dramatically increases the amount of work needed to be done by only the Heat team (hence support burden isn't shared)."}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-10-29 04:52:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

As somebody else pointed out already, there is some established adoption of Zookeeper in Nova:

https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/zk-service-heartbeat

Even absent this specific example, Nova also supports vmware, hyperv, xen, kvm, etc. etc., all without any other projects' help. Neutron supports specific hardware networking devices, Cinder works with vendors' proprietary SAN's, and Keystone can speak LDAP (which is one of the most insane protocols ever devised IMO).

Also nobody has presented a viable alternative, so even if Heat has to blaze a trail, if it enables Heat to actually scale the way we need it to, then it seems that it may be worth the extra burden. I don't support pushing it off as a 2nd class contrib plugin. If we can't scale, we're not up to OpenStack's standards, period.

I think the whole-stack-lock approach will encounter more problems than just how to do locks, and we should focus on breaking up the work-flow and serializing when needed, which can be done efficiently using job queueing and/or basic database transactions."}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-10-29 13:40:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

> If we kicked every non-python dependency out of OpenStack we'd have to write a database server, and queueing engine in python.

Right, but if we kicked every non-Python dependency that is not already being supported by other OpenStack developers (oslo.db, olso.messaging) out of Heat then... we'd be in pretty much exactly the same position we are now. It's not about "non-Python is evil", it's about "do we have the resources to support this?".

> However, if ZK is the only thing that allows real scalability, then it should be in tree and available on the same level.

If ZK is the *only* thing that allows real scalability then we should just bite the bullet, take the dependency on ZK and make that the only locking mechanism.

It would be really nice if there were a viable, less-heavyweight alternative though. As a wise man once said:

  "We are NOT using ZooKeeper."
     -- Clint Byrum, OpenStack Havana Design Summit'}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2013-10-29 19:50:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Clint,

It seems to me that depending on zookeeper for this particular feature is premature optimization.  Given all the other concerns, I'd rather *feel the pain* in terms of support of using a database lock then prematurely conclude it is insufficient for production deployments.

You mentioned some various problems with database locks.  Seems to me like we are trading a "locks become stale for 1 hour" problem with the much bigger issue of introducing a server dependency which requires HA, Scaling, Documentation, and support.  Doesn't seem like a good trade if the support burden can't be shared between other OpenStack projects.'}, {'account_id': 7253, 'date': '2013-10-29 20:43:01.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 11.'}, {'account_id': 7253, 'date': '2013-10-29 20:44:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: (1 inline comment)

I said it once, I'll say it again. Break this into two patches. It made it through becasue, IMO, reviewers were weary and rushed through bits that clearly have defects or need better documentation.

(Also, reviewers, upon feeling patch-review-weary.. perhaps +1 rather than +2..)"}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-11-14 09:55:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 21: (3 inline comments)

Clint - to be fair, he did split it up once already after you suggested that.

Arguably this could still be split into three patches:
- Add the config option for the engine_id
- Add the database calls
- Add the implementation

I'd actually be in favour of killing off the config option part altogether (see inline comments), which would go a long way toward reducing the review footprint. Once that's done I'm not sure it's an entirely bad thing that the database calls are in the same review. You'd have to look at those and the implementation together to see that we're racing.

That said, I too prefer to err on the side of too many patches."}, {'account_id': 7253, 'date': '2013-11-14 14:58:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 21: (3 inline comments)

commit_message:
Implement stack-locking for multi-engine support

Implements a distributed stack lock using the database to avoid race
conditions when multiple engines are deployed.

Blueprint multiple-engines

Change-Id: I7fba8808d8a4efbe7fd8fdff94fd9a53f3841c8b

(2 inline comments)

"}, {'account_id': 7737, 'date': '2013-11-08 14:27:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I actually think this is more complicated and may be an issue with the vanilla plugin as well.

Since the values apply to all hosts hosting the given components, I would assume that the values have to exist on those hosts (we don't have the granularity for host specific configuration at this time).  However, I don't  see any accounting for a situation in which the some node groups do have cinder volumes configured while other don't (e.g.  JOBTRACKER node group has cinder, TASKTRACKER does not).  Should the plugins be checking for uniform cinder availability? Should uniform use of cinder for HDFS or MAPRED be enforced by validation?  mapred.local.dir is used by both of the node processes.

Perhaps we follow these rules:

dfs.data.dir - storage paths on DATANODE host (don't believe it's used by NAMENODE).  
dfs.name.dir - storage paths on NAMENODE host (not used by DATANODE).
mapred.system.dir - turns out this is actually an HDFS path, not a filesystem path
mapred.local.dir - check storage paths for both JOBTRACKER and TASKTRACKER node groups (if they exist).  Use the intersection of those sets."}, {'account_id': 7109, 'date': '2013-11-08 16:31:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: No score

That is a very good point. Moreover the a single component might have 2 different storage settings if it is located on 2 or more different node groups. Say, user is allowed to run TaskTracker process on two node groups in the same cluster.

I agree with the idea to fix that by enforcing uniform use of cinder with validation. I think the validation should be plugin specific, because Vanilla plugin is not affected as it does host specific configuration.'}, {'account_id': 7737, 'date': '2013-11-11 16:58:12.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-11 17:00:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Doesn't seem to work

"}, {'account_id': 7737, 'date': '2013-11-11 17:02:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Based on some research and some discussions the values for the cinder associated hadoop properties in this commit are set as follows:

dfs.data.dir = the intersection of storage paths for all DATANODE associated node groups.  If both cinder storage paths and an ephemeral storage path exist, the ephemeral path is removed.
dfs.name.dir - the storage paths for the NAMENODE node group (validation checks already exist to ensure only on namenode in a cluster).  If both cinder storage paths and an ephemeral storage path exist, the ephemeral path is removed.
mapred.local.dir - the intersection of storage paths for all TASKTRACKER associated node groups.  If both cinder storage paths and an ephemeral storage path exist, the ephemeral path is removed. 
mapred.system.dir - this is actually an HDFS path (rather than a file system path).  The default value designated by the plugin should suffice here.'}, {'account_id': 7737, 'date': '2013-11-11 17:04:55.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 7737, 'date': '2013-11-11 17:05:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Based on some research and some discussions the values for the cinder associated hadoop properties in this commit are set as follows:
dfs.data.dir = the intersection of storage paths for all DATANODE associated node groups. If both cinder storage paths and an ephemeral storage path exist, the ephemeral path is removed. dfs.name.dir - the storage paths for the NAMENODE node group (validation checks already exist to ensure only on namenode in a cluster). If both cinder storage paths and an ephemeral storage path exist, the ephemeral path is removed. mapred.local.dir - the intersection of storage paths for all TASKTRACKER associated node groups. If both cinder storage paths and an ephemeral storage path exist, the ephemeral path is removed. mapred.system.dir - this is actually an HDFS path (rather than a file system path). The default value designated by the plugin should suffice here.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-11 17:07:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Doesn't seem to work

commit_message:
Add support for cinder to HDP plugin

Though cinder volumes can be selected thru the UI during node group
template creation, the volumes were not being utilized as expected
by the HDP plugin.

Fixes: bug #1248617

Change-Id: Ie2380a913ca8bda61fb697946941304a26f58d80

commit_message:
Update quota-set throw 500 error

The server doesn't check whether the parameter "quota_set" or
"quota_class_set" is in request
body.So the 500 error has been thrown.

We should catch the KeyError and transfer the KeyError to
400(HTTPBadRequest) instead of 500.

Change-Id: I01260c77efa50324f3d203888689cdb1e94d2c21
Closes-Bug: #1249971

commit_message:
Remove folsom-specific logic

No testing is done on OpenStack Folsom any longer, so we can clean
up devstack-gate scripts accordingly.

* devstack-vm-gate-dev.sh
* devstack-vm-gate-wrap.sh
* devstack-vm-gate.sh: Remove conditionals and variables relevant
only to stable/folsom testing.

Change-Id: I4e09c241920fb1c35138d6f34fc889b10926a0e6

commit_message:
Adds admin_password as key to be sanitized when logging

The Nova V3 API is moving to use admin_password instead of
admin_pass (both are currently in use). So adding admin_password
as a key that the value should be sanitized for when
logging.

Change-Id: I0eb66c948516624db8b770498ae541025545d981
Partial-Bug: #1247217

commit_message:
Fix URL for horizon in Debian

This patch fixes the URL for the Horizon dashboard in
Debian. It uses https, and not /horizon (but the root
of the server).

Change-Id: If12095b61ace9c5881e4421bdca042d9b5b8449b
backport: havana
(cherry picked from commit e014f10eb5b90ff522180151a223890810b1cbe8)

commit_message:
Install Guide: make sure that the admin can use the nova command

The first nova command example might be executed on a compute node by
the user, and it's likely that python-novaclient has not been installed
there. Suggest to the user to log on the controller or to install the
client.

Change-Id: I57009deb4a817966f9a37036f3230a418a5133e3
Partial-Bug: #1245946
backport: havana
(cherry picked from commit 24a9ad87a6356780a45f1d14bf740f4ff5ab81d7)

commit_message:
Install Guide: service fixes for ubuntu on neutron installation

* Open vSwitch needs a restart after the datapath module installation
* Debian/Ubuntu don't use chkconfig

backport: havana
(cherry picked from commit 91aa09ecf78a827de8b02c9ead4562a63887590d)

[{'created': '2013-06-10 17:07:11.000000000', 'message': "Removed filter which hid auto-assigned floating IPs

nova-network auto-assigned floating IPs were hidden from
the CLI and Horizon's floating IP list.  The filter responsible
for this was removed so that all floating IPs are visible from
the same location.  The API already protects against attempts
to manually disassociate an auto-assigned IP.

Fixes: bug #1017379
Change-Id: Ifb5dc24ea13d6efdccd72f301b78a3f72bca04e3
"}]
commit_message:
Removed filter which hid auto-assigned floating IPs

nova-network auto-assigned floating IPs were hidden from
the CLI and Horizon's floating IP list.  The filter responsible
for this was removed so that all floating IPs are visible from
the same location.  The API already protects against attempts
to manually disassociate an auto-assigned IP.

Fixes: bug #1017379
Change-Id: Ifb5dc24ea13d6efdccd72f301b78a3f72bca04e3

I think you could do something like this: https://github.com/openstack/oslo-incubator/blob/master/tests/unit/test_log.py#L182 to verify that the output is correct.  Basically it logs to a stream and then verifies the stream's contents."}, {'account_id': 7537, 'date': '2013-11-12 13:37:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (1 inline comment)

Working on the logging test now. Thanks for the heads up.'}, {'account_id': 7537, 'date': '2013-11-12 13:49:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Actually, reading through that file I find https://github.com/openstack/oslo-incubator/blob/master/tests/unit/test_log.py#L392 which tests that the log format is what you expect it to be when it is passed to the context formatter - as this already has the correct format for this change, will it not suffice?'}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2013-11-12 21:32:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: (1 inline comment)

That's overriding the default though, right?  Since we need to verify that the default is correct I think we still need a test that uses that value.

Also, I'd prefer to verify that the output is correct, not just the format string (which I think is what it's doing there).  One could add a passing test using the old format string but still get the incorrect behavior if it was just verifying that the format string is what gets set in the default.

Unfortunately, I think that could be tricky to do because of the timestamp.  At a glance, I don't think we can override the current timestamp because it's done by the stdlib so it's not using our timeutils.  The only good option I see to verify the behavior is through a regex or something that checks there is punctuation in the correct spots, and no extra fields like before.

dims, does that sound about like what you were looking for?"}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2013-11-12 21:36:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Does the default format of asctime depend on the locale? Do we need to specify the datefmt argument to the logging formatter (http://docs.python.org/2/library/logging.html#logging.Formatter) to ensure a consistent format everywhere?"}, {'account_id': 7537, 'date': '2013-11-13 13:18:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Doug: http://docs.python.org/2/library/time.html#time.asctime: "Locale information is not used by asctime()."'}, {'account_id': 7537, 'date': '2013-11-13 13:26:41.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-13 13:30:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Works for me

Build succeeded.

- gate-oslo-incubator-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/72/55672/4/check/gate-oslo-incubator-pep8/9191660 : SUCCESS in 1m 34s
